   <TITLE> Bikestuff</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="marble.gif">

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Matts HTML Garage.</H2>

<H3>My 1st Bike: A 1986 Honda CBR 250F</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/cbr250_1.jpg">Side
view<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/cbr250_2.jpg">Front
View</A></P>

<P> It was a nice bike. Redlined at 17 000 rpm. Stood up to my abusing
the clutch the first few days as I learnt to ride.<BR>
250 fours are actually quite easy to ride, as they have predictable power
(ie very little) and good handling/braking.<BR>
The downside is when this happens...</P>

<P> <A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/cbr250_3.jpg">Ouch<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/cbr_4.jpg">I
think these are bent</A></P>

<P> ...it tends to cost a lot...to the blind git who backed out it front
of me I&nbsp;might add!</P>

<P> </P>

<H3>My 2nd and current bike: A 1988 Suzuki GSXR 250</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/gsxr_1.jpg">Side
on<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/gsxr_2.jpg">Naked!<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/gsxr_3.jpg">Other
side<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/gsxr_4.jpg">Nice,
clean discs, eh?</A></P>

<P> The GSXR photos were all taken before I started to spend money on it...so
don't laugh! But is is a nice bike, even though it still is a bit tatty
(it's in dire need of a new paint job). </P>

<H3>My 3rd Bike: Britten V-1100</H3>

<P><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/brit_1.jpg">Side
on<BR>
</A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/brit_2.jpg">3/4
view</A></P>

<P> Well It was mine for 2 whole hours while I &quot;supervised&quot; it
at a open day at the School of Engineering. That particular Britten was
one of the V-1100's, the model before the V-1000, distigushed by the blockly
front suspension and the straight through exhaust. It is used by the company
as the display model as the internals of the motor and some parts of the
frame are seriously shot. </P>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH=50% SIZE=3><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/matt/matt.htm">Back
home</A> </P></CENTER>

