<HEAD>
<TITLE>Exercise GE1: GEOMETRIC MODELLING -- OVERVIEW OF LEGO(tm) PERSON</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<H1>Exercise GE1 (cont.): LEGO(tm) PERSON<P>
OVERVIEW ____ A multi-part assembly</H1>

<!-- next filename.gif should have same stem as present filename.html -->
<IMG SRC="person.gif">
<HR>
<!-- next nextfile.html must match next file in series -->
<A HREF="lego_head.html"><IMG SRC="skip.gif"></A><P>

<H2><A NAME="start">Contents (`OVERVIEW OF LEGO PERSON'):</A></H2>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#intro">INTRODUCTION</A>
<LI><A HREF="#how_much_detail">HOW MUCH DETAIL IS REQUIRED ?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#assessment_note">A NOTE ABOUT ASSESSMENT</A>
<LI><A HREF="#parts_summary">A SUMMARY OF THE LEGO BODY PARTS</A>
</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="intro">INTRODUCTION:</A></H3>

The instructions which follow describe the creation of a series of related
3D models.  These models correspond to the various body parts of a standard
LEGO person.  <EM>LEGO</EM> is a registered trademark of LEGO Australia
Pty Ltd.<P>

The LEGO person was chosen as a modelling subject because:

<UL>
<LI>it is likely to be familiar to many engineering students;
<LI>its shape is composed of a range of relatively simple geometrical
    primitives, but is sufficiently complex to maintain interest;
<LI>it is possible to <EM>lend</EM> (not donate!) each student a sample
    LEGO person for study and measurement during the class exercise;
<LI>some of the body parts are harder to model than others, so learners
    can progress through a range of degrees of difficulty;
<LI>the various body parts can be combined in Pro/ENGINEER into an
    assembly, giving insight into the hierarchy of features, parts, and
    assemblies.
</UL>

It is assumed that you have completed the `steel bracket' model
described in earlier notes, and have thereby become acquainted with some
basic feature-creation operations in Pro/ENGINEER.<P>

You are now invited to tackle the challenging task of devising your own
3D models.  Some help will be given along the way in these instructions,
but not in as much detail as before.  It is hoped that you will begin to
recognise familiar patterns of layout and activity in Pro/ENGINEER's
interface, and so become more independent and confident in your use of it.
Eventually you will become an experienced modeller, and 3D modelling will
become `second-nature' to you, but it will take some practice.<P>

This document  merely introduces the LEGO body parts.  Linked documents
contain more specific instructions for creating each part, and eventually
for assembling the entire LEGO person.  However we expect that few students,
if any, will finish all the parts within the allotted class time.  Some
keen people may wish to complete the modelling exercise later.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="how_much_detail">HOW MUCH DETAIL IS REQUIRED ?:</A></H3>

Even though the body parts of a LEGO person have <EM>relatively</EM> simple
basic shapes, each one of the parts would be very difficult for you to
model <EM>if you attempt to represent all geometrical details</EM>.  In
all cases, it is recommended that you make some simplifications to the
parts you are modelling.  Obviously, some judgement will be needed in
deciding how far to simplify, and the pictures in these notes are intended
to help you with this.  As a general rule, for example, don't put too many
rounds on your parts (even though just about every edge on a piece of LEGO
is rounded).

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="assessment_note">A NOTE ABOUT ASSESSMENT:</A></H3>

A few formal questions (for answering on paper) may be asked through
the course of these instruction.  Where these occur in a particular
instruction file, there will be a clear indication in the `Contents'
section at the beginning of that file, to alert you to the existence of
the questions.<P>

Mainly, however, the assessment of your work will be based on the models
which you create.  It is vital, therefore, that you <EM>SAVE YOUR WORK</EM>
as you proceed.  Remember to save each part whenever a new feature is
created, and keep a note of the names you give to the various parts.<P>

There will not be sufficient time for your tutor to assess your work in
class, so it will be necessary for you to submit a copy of each of your
model files into a specially created directory for later assessment.  This
directory is unique for each student: for example, a student whose login
name (i.e. the name of their DECR account) is `jsmith' should save his or
her final Pro/ENGINEER parts into the directory /home/common/me/jsmith.
Their `bracket' part should be saved as /home/common/me/jsmith/bracket, 
and similarly for each of the later parts created for this exercise.
The <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B> command is used to achieve this.<P>

Only the final version of each of your parts should be submitted to the
special directory.  Note that in the case of parts created during the
first session (last week), you will need to <B>Search/Retr</B> these
from the relevant sub-directory within your home directory (normally
this will be the sub-directory you named `3D'), and then do a
<B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B> from the MAIN menu to save it to the special
submission directory.<P>

Details of these arrangements for the submission of work for assessment 
are explained on a separate handout sheet.  Please read it carefully,
and ask your tutor for help if you have any difficulty submitting files.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="parts_summary">A SUMMARY OF THE LEGO BODY PARTS:</A></H3>

The body parts of the standard LEGO(tm) person may be summarised as:
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="lego_head.html">the head
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_head.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_torso.html">the torso
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_torso.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_hips.html">the hips
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_hips.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_leg_r.html">the right leg
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_leg_r.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_leg_l.html">the left leg
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_leg_l.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_arms.html">the arms
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_arms.gif"></A>
<LI><A HREF="lego_hand.html">the hand (two of them)
                       <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="mini_hand.gif"></A>
</OL>

It is recommended that you attempt modelling the body parts in the same
sequence as listed above, as this represents an increasing level of
difficulty.  Don't worry about the arms -- these have a very complex
shape, and it is not expected that any student should try to model them
(although you may want to have a look at the arm which we have created
for you).<P>

You can use the links on the mini-images above to go directly to the
instruction files for each part, or you can work through the files in
sequence by using the `forwards arrow' button, below (it looks like 
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="fwd.gif">).<P>

Alternatively, if you get lost, you can always use the `Home' button at
the bottom of this Mosaic window to return to the original Home Page for 
exercise GE1, and use the links in the Instructions Directory there.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<HR>
