<H1>Exercise GE1: HOW TO USE Mosaic IN GE1</H1>

<!-- next filename.gif should have same stem as present filename.html -->
<IMG SRC="mosaic_intro.gif">
<HR>
<!-- next nextfile.html must match next file in series -->
<A HREF="overview.html"><IMG SRC="skip.gif"></A><P>


<H2><A NAME="start">Contents (`HOW TO USE Mosaic IN GE1'):</A></H2>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#mosaic_is">WHAT IS MOSAIC ?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#doc_structure">HOW ARE THESE INSTRUCTIONS ORGANISED ?</A>
<LI><A HREF="#how_it_works">A MINIMUM SET OF INSTRUCTIONS FOR TODAY</A>
<LI><A HREF="#many_windows">COPING WITH ALL THESE WINDOWS</A>
</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="mosaic_is">WHAT IS MOSAIC ?:</A></H3>

NCSA Mosaic is an information browser developed at the National
Center for Supercomputing Applications at the University of Illinois,
Urbana-Champaign.<P>

Mosaic is an Internet-based global hypermedia browser that allows you to
discover, retrieve, and display documents and data from all over the
Internet.<P>

Mosaic is part of the World Wide Web project, a distributed hypermedia
environment originated at CERN and collaborated upon by a large,
informal, and international design and development team. 
Mosaic helps you explore a huge and rapidly expanding universe of
information and gives you powerful new capabilities for interacting with
information.<P>

The term `global hypermedia' means that information located around the world
is interconnected in an environment that allows you to travel through the
information by clicking on hyperlinks -- terms, icons, or images in
documents that point to other, related documents or parts of documents.<P>

Any hyperlink can point to any document anywhere on the Internet.
For example, this little image contains a link to a larger image.<P>
Click (only <EM>once</EM>) on the icon to see its linked document ...  
<A HREF="http://www.mame.mu.oz.au/eng_design/GE1/GENERAL/rn_stimpy.gif">
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="garbage.gif"></A><P>

You can play with this stuff for hours.  Please don't do this today -- 
you have more important work to do!  Mosaic is just a tool.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="doc_structure">HOW ARE THESE INSTRUCTIONS ORGANISED ?:</A></H3>

Perhaps the structure of the on-line instructions for this exercise seems 
a bit mysterious to you.  It is really not that complicated!  Except for the
Home Page, all of the instruction files are organised in the same way.<P>

The Home Page is a very short file.  It contains links to all the other
files which make up the set of instructions for Computer Graphics Exercise
GE1.  You can get to the start of every other file from the Home Page.<P>

All other information for GE1 is organised as a set of <EM>documents</EM>
(or computer files), each of which is divided into several <EM>sections</EM>.
Each document begins with a prominent heading and a characteristic picture
to help you recognise the document.  Then there follows a `Contents:' section.
The Contents in any given document contains convenient links to all the
section headings within the same document, although you can always get to
those sections just by scrolling down the document window, using the Mosaic
scroll-bar.<P>

There is a link button at the end of each section which can take you back to
the beginning of the same document (so you can use the Contents links easily).
There is also a different link button at the end of each <EM>document</EM>
which enables you to jump to the next document in the series.  For
convenience, a similar link has been placed near the start of each document
to allow you to quickly `skip ahead' to the next document in the series (this
`Skip' link button looks like a horizontal green bar across the Mosaic window
-- you've probably seen it already).<P>

There are about ten separate documents in this entire series of instructions.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="how_it_works">A MINIMUM SET OF INSTRUCTIONS FOR TODAY:</A></H3>

<UL>
<LI>Underlined pieces of text are links.  They will take you to other parts
    of this series of instructions.
<LI>Sometimes links take you to new files, sometimes to a different place
    in the same file.  There will usually be text in or near the link to
    tell you where the link will take you.
    <A HREF="nowhere.html">This link will take you nowhere special.</A>
<LI>When you have used a link, its appearance changes (here the underline
    becomes dashed, and the colour changes from blue to purple -- yuk!).
<LI>You can move up or down in the same file by using the Scroll Bar along
    the right-hand side of this Mosaic window.
<LI>The button labeled `Back' at the lower left corner of this Mosaic
    window will take you back to the previous place from which you jumped.
<LI>The button labeled `Home' has been set up so that it will always take
    you back to the master Instructions Directory, called your `Home Page'.
    If you ever get `lost in hyperspace', you can always go back home.
<LI>At the end of each main section of each file, an icon-button has been
    provided so you can easily return to the start of the same file (where
    you can use the links in the Contents area to jump to another section
    of the same file if you want to).  Usually you will want to go keep
    working down the file rather than jumping back to the start, but these
    `Return' buttons are there just in case.
    They look like this: <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"> . . . but this one
    is just a picture.  Sorry!
<LI>At the end of every file there is another icon-button like this:
    <IMG SRC="fwd.gif">  These are to help you move quickly to
    the next file in the series without having to go via the Home Page.
    Again, they are just provided for your convenience.
<LI>It is recommended that you work through these documents in the 
    sequence presented, although you don't <EM>have</EM> to.  However, the
    instructions for Pro/ENGINEER parts will develop in a logical
    progression, so you might miss something if you hop about.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="many_windows">COPING WITH ALL THESE WINDOWS:</A></H3>

There are a lot of windows to think about in this exercise, aren't there?
If you have made it this far, then you are probably managing them OK.
Nevertheless, it might be helpful to summarise here what we will call the
`standard' arrangement of windows and icons on the screen.  We have found
this `standard' arrangement to be the most workable layout for doing
computer graphics exercise such as this one, where you need to use:
<UL>
<LI>the Pro/ENGINEER windows,
<LI>this Mosaic window,
<LI>and perhaps a UNIX shell window
</UL>
all at the same time.  Just as a reminder, the Pro/ENGINEER windows and menus
look generally like the following figure:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="pro_windows_1.gif"><P>
... except that with some windowing environments, the Close Box is in a
different location, as shown below:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="pro_windows_2.gif"><P>

The `standard' arrangement of the various kinds of windows and their closed
icons is as summarised in the following diagram.<P>
<IMG SRC="std_windows.gif"><P>

Try developing a working style in which you have the Pro/ENGINEER and Mosaic
windows open simultaneously, and the UNIX shell window closed, so that your
arrangement of windows and their closed icons looks like this:<P>
<IMG SRC="work_windows.gif"><P>

You can be reading from the Mosaic window, and close it temporarily whenever
you need unobstructed access to the Pro/ENGINEER windows.  If you need to
bring all the Pro/ENGINEER windows and menus to the front quickly, this can
be achieved by iconising and immediately re-opening its graphics window.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<HR>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
