<HEAD>
<TITLE>Exercise GE1: GEOMETRIC MODELLING -- OVERVIEW</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<H1>Exercise GE1: OVERVIEW</H1>

<IMG SRC="overview.gif">
<HR>
<!-- next nextfile.html must match next file in series -->
<A HREF="troubles.html"><IMG SRC="skip.gif"></A><P>


<H2><A NAME="start">Contents (`GE1 OVERVIEW'):</A></H2>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#objectives">OBJECTIVES OF COMPUTER GRAPHICS EXERCISE GE1:</A>
<LI><A HREF="#user_interfaces">USER INTERFACES FOR CAD SOFTWARE:</A>
<LI><A HREF="#menu_system">USING Pro/ENGINEER's MENU SYSTEM:</A>
<LI><A HREF="#notation_conventions">
    NOTATION CONVENTIONS FOR THESE INSTRUCTIONS:</A>
    <UL>
    <LI><A HREF="#menu_titles"> menu titles</A>
    <LI><A HREF="#command_select"> command selection</A>
    <LI><A HREF="#command_strings"> strings of commands</A>
    <LI><A HREF="#screen_picks"> picking from the screen</A>
    <LI><A HREF="#kbd_entry"> entry from the keyboard</A>
    </UL>
<LI><A HREF="#miscellaneous">OTHER ISSUES ...</A>
</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="objectives">OBJECTIVES OF COMPUTER GRAPHICS EXERCISE GE1:</A></H3>

The aims of this exercise are:
<UL>
<LI>to introduce you to a serious 3D-modelling package (Pro/ENGINEER);
<LI>to gain an overview of basic concepts involved in using Pro/ENGINEER:
    <UL>
    <LI> feature-based modelling;
    <LI> parent/child relationships between features;
    <LI> the modelling hierarchy (features within parts within assemblies);
    </UL>
<LI>to use some of the main types of feature available within Pro/ENGINEER:
    <UL>
    <LI> datums (planes and axes);
    <LI> extruded, revolved and swept protrusions;
    <LI> extruded, revolved and swept cuts;
    <LI> rounds;
    <LI> shells;
    <LI> maybe some others (e.g. holes);
    </UL>
<LI>to give you the satisfaction and experience of creating your own simple
    parts and assemblies;
<LI>to point you towards on-line manuals for developing your knowledge of
    Pro/ENGINEER in your own time.
</UL>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="user_interfaces">USER INTERFACES FOR CAD SOFTWARE:</A></H3>

For computer software to be useful, you need to be able to tell it what you
want it to do.  A user interface is the means by which communication is
achieved between a computer program and you, its user.  Many CAD software
packages employ graphical user interfaces or command-line interfaces, or some
combination of both.  Graphical user interfaces are usually icon-based, and
have pull-down menus, dialogue boxes and various kinds of on-screen buttons. 
Command-line interfaces require the user to type commands as text in the
proper syntax.  Both systems have their advantages and their disadvantages,
their advocates and their detractors.<P>
By contrast, Pro/ENGINEER relies on a menu-based user interface, with the
occasional entry of data (text or dimensions) through the keyboard.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="menu_system">USING Pro/ENGINEER's MENU SYSTEM:</A></H3>

Pro/ENGINEER is driven largely by menu selections from its hierarchical
system of menus.  Each selection is made by using the left mouse button to
`select' a command which is listed in a menu.  These are not 'pull-down' menus 
-- instead, the appropriate menu(s) will appear on the screen in response to
selections from higher-level menus.  Usually the most likely menu for making
your next selection will be the one which Pro/ENGINEER places nearest to the
bottom of the screen, although you may override this and select from a
higher-level menu.  Unavailable choices on a menu are greyed out.  Sometimes
several command choices must be made on the one menu -- each currently
selected choice will be highlighted in red.  Many menus appear with the
default selection(s) already highlighted (in red).

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="notation_conventions">
    NOTATION CONVENTIONS FOR THESE INSTRUCTIONS:</A></H3>
In these instructions we will need to use a standard notation for describing
menu selections compactly.  The conventions are as follows.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="menu_titles"> Menu Titles</A></H4>
Menu titles such as PART and FEAT and ENTERPART are shown in uppercase
letters, but with no other special formatting.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="command_select"> Command Selection</A></H4>
Menu commands (i.e. the items listed in the menu) are shown in <B>Bold</B>
with their first letter capitalised (this is the same way that the
commands appear in the menu).  Examples are
<B>Regenerate</B> and <B>Done</B> and <B>Thru All</B>.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="command_strings"> Strings of commands</A></H4>
Command strings, which are a series of menu selections, are shown with
each item separated either by an arrow (designated by &quot;-&gt;&quot;,
without the quotes) or a pipe character (you know, a &quot;|&quot; vertical
bar, without the quotes).  The arrows indicate that you move from one menu
to another, while the pipe separates choices you make within the one menu.
A typical command string is:<P>
        <B>Create -&gt; Solid -&gt; Cut -&gt; Extrude | Solid | Done -&gt;
	Single | Done -&gt; One Side -&gt; Thru All | Done</B>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="screen_picks"> Picking from the screen</A></H4>
In these notes, the word `pick' will be used exclusively to refer to 
cases where you point to an object on the Pro/ENGINEER graphics window,
and click on it (usually with the LEFT mouse button).  Pro/ENGINEER 
generally highlights such objects by changing their colour.


<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="kbd_entry"> Entry from the keyboard</A></H4>
Additional conventions are needed to handle data entry from the keyboard.
When you need to answer a computer prompt, these instructions will show the
prompt and your response as follows:<P>

<KBD>Prompt [default_value]: <B>user_entry</B></KBD><P>

For example:<P>
<KBD>Enter Part name [PRT0001]: <B>wheel &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

In the example above, the text
&quot;<KBD>Enter Part name [PRT001]:</KBD>&quot;
is the exact prompt from the computer (note that Pro/ENGINEER uses square
brackets &quot;[...]&quot; to indicate default responses), and the text  
&quot;<KBD>wheel</KBD>&quot;
(without the quotes) is your intended response.<P>

The characters &quot;&lt;CR&gt;&quot; stand for `carriage return', and they
mean `type the key marked [RETURN] (or [ENTER] on some keyboards)'.  The
notion of a `carriage return' dates from the era of mechanical typewriters!<P>

Variables for which the user must substitute a particular value are
shown in input text as italicised variable names, for example:
<VAR>filename</VAR>.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="miscellaneous">OTHER ISSUES ...</A></H3>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4>Saving Your Work</H4>
Pro/ENGINEER does not automatically save your work, or even prompt you
to save it before Exiting.  Unless you consciously save your work at
suitable points in its development, your work will be lost when you
Exit Pro/ENGINEER.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4>An Educational Experiment</H4>
This is a very new exercise, and in some ways you are part of an
educational experiment.  Don't worry if you feel that your progress is
somewhat slow through the various tasks in these instructions.  You are
learning how to use a state-of-the-art 3D modelling system, and that is no
mean feat!  Feel free to use Pro/ENGINEER outside your usual class times
if you want to work further through these instructions (to finish the
LEGO person, for example).  But you don't have to spend more than the 
allotted four hours on it.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4>Access to Pro/ENGINEER</H4>
You may want to use Pro/ENGINEER at other times throughout your course.
Go for it!  Expertise developed on a system like this will certainly 
enhance your professional qualifications (and also make you very impatient
with the less powerful CAD packages you might have to use elsewhere!), so
we want to encourage you to use Pro/ENGINEER wherever it suits you.
Information on how to learn more about using the software is provided
at the conclusion of this instruction set.<P>

It is intended that Pro/ENGINEER will become widely accessible around the
University -- especially throughout the Faculty of Engineering.  DECR is
one of the main centres providing access.  However the University has
negotiated a site-licence for this software, so if your own department is
not currently running it, and you want to use it, why not have a word to
your friendly Head of Department and suggest that they participate?
Details may be obtained by sending e-mail to:

<ADDRESS>
pro-query@mame.mu.OZ.AU
</ADDRESS>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A><P>


<HR>
