<HR>
<H3><A NAME="intro">PROBLEMS ?!? . . . WHAT PROBLEMS ?:</A></H3>

We have found that students encounter some common problems when attempting
this computer graphics exercise.  The purpose of this `trouble-shooting'
document is to provide an easily accessible place for you to find information
about these problems.  You can jump back to here (via the Home Page) whenever
you need help.<P>

The problems form a somewhat miscellaneous collection.  Browse them now so
you have some idea of the difficulties covered.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="mosaic">PROBLEMS READING THE MOSAIC INSTRUCTIONS:</A></H3>

<DL>

<DT>``I am lost.''
<DD>Push the button labeled `Home' at the bottom of the Mosaic window.  This
    will return you to a consistent starting point.  From there you can can
    jump easily to all other parts of the instructions.<P>

<DT>``How do I get rid of extra Mosaic windows ?''
<DD>Push the button labeled `Close Window'.  This actually quits the window,
    so the word `close' is a bit misleading, we think.<P>

<DT>``How do I quit out of Mosaic ?''
<DD>Push the button labeled `Close Window' in all open Mosaic windows.<P>

<DT>``The Mosaic window is the wrong size.''
<DD>Re-size it by locating the mouse pointer over a corner (or edge) of the
    Mosaic window, and using the left mouse-button to drag the window to be
    a different size.<P>

<DT>``The Mosaic window is in the wrong place.''
<DD>Move it to a different location by locating the mouse pointer over the
    title-bar of the Mosaic window, and using the left mouse-button to drag
    the window into a different location.<P>

<DT>``My Mosaic window is in the way.''
<DD>Instead of re-sizing or moving it, you could simply iconise the Mosaic
    window temporarily by clicking on the small close box in the title-bar.
    This is the box which contains either a small dot, or a small
    downwards-facing triangle.  The icon can be re-opened by double-clicking
    on it.<P>

<DT>``I have lost parts of the Mosaic window.''
<DD>Perhaps you have placed the window so that it is partly beyond the edges
    of the screen -- if so, drag the window to a place where you can see all
    four borders clearly.<P>
    Perhaps you have made the Mosaic window so small that some of the
    buttons along its lower edge are no longer visible.  If so, re-size the
    Mosaic window as described above.<P>

<DT>``Some of the images look like this ... <IMG SRC="nonexistent.gif.html">''
<DD>This is our fault, not yours.
    Either there is something wrong with the way the image has been set up,
    or we just haven't gotten around to creating the image yet.  One thing
    you can try is to press the `Reload' button at the bottom of the Mosaic
    window.  If this doesn't work, inform your tutor.

</DL>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="unix">UNIX AND ACCOUNT PROBLEMS:</A></H3>

<DL>

<DT>``My password has expired.''
<DT>``I have forgotten my password.''
<DT>``I don't have a DECR account.''
<DD>We assume that, since you are reading these instructions at the computer,
    you don't have any of the above problems!  If somehow you do, then see
    one of the DECR staff (preferably the Duty Programmer).<P>

<DT>``There are heaps of files in my directory.''
<DD>Use sub-directories to group related files together, and to separate them
    from other files.  It is beyond the scope of these notes to teach you
    UNIX, but it's amazing what you can accomplish with a working knowledge
    of just a few UNIX commands.  Check out commands like <B>ls</B>, 
    <B>mkdir</B>, <B>cd</B>, <B>cp</B>, <B>mv</B>, <B>rm</B>.  Be careful
    of the last one, since it removes files from the disk.<P>

<DT>``I cannot find the file I saved earlier.''
<DD>Maybe you are looking in the wrong directory.  Is your current working
    directory the same as when you saved the file?  Use <B>cd</B> to `move
    around' the filesystem, and use <B>ls</B> to list the files contained
    in directories.<P>

<DT>``I accidentally removed a file which I now need.''
<DD>Hmmmm.  It's probably gone forever.  If you are lucky, the DECR staff
    might be able to restore yesterday's version from a backup tape.<P>

<DT>``My disk storage quota has been exceeded.''
<DD>You will need to remove some files from your directory.  Keep your
    directories tidy and clear of junk (i.e. unnecessary files).

</DL>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="hardware">HARDWARE PERFORMANCE PROBLEMS:</A></H3>

<DL>

<DT>``What kind of workstation am I using ?''
<DD>If you are in a DECR laboratory, and are working at a colour workstation,
    chances are that you are using either a Silicon Graphics (SG) Indy, or
    a Sun SPARC 2.  The SG Indys have a blue box, the Suns have a grey box.
    The SG Indys have a slightly smaller screen than the Suns.<P>

<DT>``My Sun workstation seems very slow when I run Pro/ENGINEER.''
<DD>That's right!  Certain operations (e.g. spinning shaded images) happen
    very slowly on the Suns.  There is not much you can do about it, as
    the DECR Sun workstations are not optimised for high-speed graphics.
    It is possible that other people are remotely logged into your computer
    and slowing your work down, but you don't have much control over that.
    Try to avoid shaded images as much as possible.<P>

<DT>``My SG Indy workstation seems very slow when I run Pro/ENGINEER.''
<DD>Probably you are not logged into the SG Indy under the `xterm' option.
    The SG Indys are equipped with powerful graphics capabilities, and can
    run Pro/ENGINEER very effectively -- even when manipulating shaded
    images.  However in order to make use of these capabilities, you need
    to do two things:
    <UL>
    <LI>have a special `SG' account created for you by DECR staff.  At the
        moment, this privilege is restricted to first-year students doing
        Technology 2, or the CAD option in IDM;
    <LI>connect to the Indy using the `xterm' option at login time.
    </UL>
    It is worth logging out and in again if you have an `SG' account, as
    the graphics performance will improve greatly.<P>

<DT>``My workstation seems to be not responding -- can I switch it off ?''
<DD>No!  Never switch off any part of these workstations.  It is more than
likely that your Pro/ENGINEER session is prompting for some keyboard input,
anyway.

</DL>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="proeng">PROBLEMS USING Pro/ENGINEER:</A></H3>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="starting"> Starting Pro/ENGINEER</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``How do I start Pro/ENGINEER in the background ?''
<DD>By typing `<B><KBD>proeng &</KBD></B>' (without quotes, and followed by
    a return) in a UNIX shell window.<P>

<DT>``I think I may have started Pro/ENGINEER twice!  How can I check ?''
<DD>The best way to check is to iconise (i.e. close) all windows.  There
should be only one Pro/ENGINEER icon visible on the screen.  If there are
more, open the Pro/ENGINEER sessions (by double-clicking the icon) one at
a time, and <B>Exit</B> (and confirm) all but the one you want to keep.<P>

<DT>``Where does Pro/ENGINEER save my models ?''
<DD>Pro/ENGINEER will save files into its current working directory, which
    is (initially) the directory you were in when you started Pro/ENGINEER.
    This is also the directory in which it looks for files.  For this reason
    it is a good idea to change to this directory (within UNIX) 
    <EM>before</EM> starting your Pro/ENGINEER session.

</DL>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="windows_menus"> Managing Pro/ENGINEER windows and menus</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``Can I re-size the Pro/ENGINEER main graphics window ?''
<DD>Yes, but it's not recommended.<P>

<DT>``Is it safe to move the Pro/ENGINEER menus around ?''
<DD>No, it is a bad idea.  The menus are intended to cascade down the screen
    in a logical progression, and their clarity depends on their location
    on the screen.  You run the risk of confusion if you move the menus from
    their default locations.<P>

<DT>``How do I see more lines in the Pro/ENGINEER message window ?''
<DD>Click carefully on the border of the message window to bring it to the
    `front' of the screen (i.e. so that it appears in front of the graphics
    window).  You can scroll up the message window if you want to.  Return
    the graphics window to the front again by clicking on its title-bar.

</DL>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="retrieving"> Retrieving saved models</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``How do I retrieve previously-saved models ?''
<DD>The easiest way to retrieve files is to use the <B>Search/Retr</B>
    facility.  This avoids the need to type anything!  If you accidentally
    select <B>Retrieve</B>, you can still bring up a menu of available
    objects to retrieve by typing a question mark (`?') in response to
    the prompt.<P> 

<DT>``What if I can't find the model I want in the current directory ?''
<DD>It is possible to navigate around the directory levels from within
    the <B>Search/Retr</B> facility of Pro/ENGINEER.  To `go up' the
    directory hierarchy, simply select <B>UP..</B> from the menu showing
    the contents of the searched directory.  To `go down', select the name
    of a sub-directory from the same menu (all sub-directories are
    shown with a leading slash `/').  Note that this navigation is for 
    single retrievals only -- the current working directory is unchanged.<P>

<DT>``Help!  The model I retrieved is missing some features ...''
<DD>This probably means that you didn't save the latest version of your
    model, so that the latest features were lost when you last exited
    Pro/ENGINEER.  Alternatively, you may have saved your model into more
    than one directory, so that you might be retrieving a version of the
    model which is not the most recent on disk (i.e. you started Pro/ENGINEER
    from a directory containing out-of-date files).  The best thing to do
    is to <B>Exit</B> Pro/ENGINEER without saving anything, and search your
    directories and sub-directories for the latest version of your part.

</DL>
<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="focus"> Getting back to the PART menu</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``I seem to have lost the PART menu ! !''
<DD><I>Short answer:</I> use <B>Change Window</B> from the MAIN menu.<P>
    <I>Long Answer:</I>
    It is very common for students to get into a mode in which they can 
    see their part in the graphics window, but are unable to access the
    PART menu in order to work on the part.  This is called `losing focus',
    and occurs because you selected <B>Mode</B> from the MAIN menu while
    you had an active part on the screen.  When you do this, Pro/ENGINEER 
    thinks you want to work on a second model simultaneously with the 
    first, and so brings up the MODE menu.  In this way you can have
    several Pro/ENGINEER graphics windows on the screen, each containing a 
    different model (this can be very useful, but it is probably not what
    you want right now!).  To return `focus' to a particular part (e.g. 
    the one in the main graphics window), select <B>Change Window</B> from
    the MAIN menu, and pick on the window which you want to activate.
    The corresponding PART menu should then appear.<P>

<DT>``How do I get rid of an unwanted graphics window ?''
<DD>Select <B>Quit Window</B> from the MAIN menu, and pick on the window
    which you want to clear.  The part in that window will then disappear.
    Note that the part remains resident in Pro/ENGINEER's memory until
    you <B>Exit</B> completely from Pro/ENGINEER.  In the meantime, you
    can re-activate it by selecting <B>Mode -&gt; Part -&gt; Search/Retr
    -&gt; In Session</B>.

</DL>
<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="orientation"> Orienting the sketching view</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``Why must I to provide a <EM>horizontal or vertical reference for
    sketching</EM> each time I want to sketch anything ?''
<DD>Think of the sketching plane as a sheet of paper which Pro/ENGINEER is
    going to present to you in the plane of the screen.  Pro/ENGINEER needs
    to know which way to orient the paper.  The way you tell it this 
    information is by choosing a <EM>reference plane</EM> (which must be
    perpendicular to the sketching plane), and nominating the direction
    which this reference plane will be facing (either to the <B>Top</B>, 
    the <B>Bottom</B>, the <B>Right</B>, or the <B>Left</B> of the screen)
    when the sketching plane is facing out towards you from the screen.<P>

<IMG SRC="ref_planes.gif"><P>

<DT>``What is meant by the <EM>direction</EM> of the reference plane ?''
<DD>For a datum plane, the direction is indicated by the vector pointing
    outwards from the yellow side of the datum plane.  For a solid face,
    the direction is that of the outward normal to the surface.

</DL>
<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="sketcher"> Using the Sketcher</A></H4>
<DL>

<DT>``How do I start sketching with the mouse ?''
<DD>Select <B>Sketch -&gt; Mouse Sketch</B> from the SKETCHER menu.<P>

<DT>``Which buttons do what when <B>Mouse Sketch</B> is selected ?''
<DD>The LEFT mouse-button sketches a chain of lines (use MIDDLE button
    to exit line-creation).<P>
    The MIDDLE mouse-button sketches circles (use MIDDLE button again to
    finish the circle, and LEFT button to abort).<P>
    The RIGHT mouse-button sketches tangent arcs from the end-points of 
    existing lines or arcs (use RIGHT button again to finish the arc,
    and MIDDLE button to abort).<P>

<DT>``How do I create centrelines, and what are they for ?''
<DD>Select <B>Sketch -&gt; Line -&gt; Centreline</B>, starting from the
     SKETCHER menu.  The purpose of centrelines is to impose some form
     of symmetry or alignment on various elements of a sketch, so the
     term `centreline' should not be taken too literally.<P>

<DT>``What is an <EM>open section</EM> ?''
<DD>An open section has some lines (or arcs) whose ends are not connected
    to any other sketched geometry.<P>

<DT>``My sketched section looks closed, but Pro/ENGINEER says it is open.''
<DD>Either your sketch is too untidy so that some line ends were not 
    assumed to be connected to each other, or you have drawn some lines
    superimposed on other lines, so they look like a single line.<P>

<DT>``The screen looks messy after several items were deleted.  How can I
    clean it up ?''
<DD>From the MAIN menu, select <B>View -&gt; Regen View</B>.

</DL>
<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
