</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="oview">OVERVIEW OF THIS PART:</A></H3>

Using the instructions in this file, you will create a 3D computer model
of the Steel Bracket illustrated above.  This model will contain several
<EM>features</EM> (indeed, one of our aims is to clarify the notion of
what a `feature' is).  Even though there are many features, the entire
bracket is considered to be a single <EM>part</EM> since it is composed
of continuous material.<P>

The bracket is a fairly challenging part for a novice modeller, and may
take you some time to construct.  We estimate that you may need about
90 minutes (i.e. most of your first session).  An experienced user of
Pro/ENGINEER might take 5 minutes for the same task.  Don't be
disheartened by this -- your proficiency will rapidly increase!<P>

Start creating your Bracket part now.  If you still have the image of
the cylinder in the main graphics window, clear it by selecting
<B>Quit Window</B> from the MAIN menu.  Notice that when you do this,
the PART menu disappears to be replaced by the MODE window so that you
are ready to create a new part in the (now empty) graphics window.<P>

Now from the MODE menu, select <B>Part -&gt; Create</B><P>

Notice that you are being prompted in Pro/ENGINEER's message window.
In response to this you should type the name `bracket' (without quotes)
as the name of your new part. In standard notation:

<P><KBD>Enter Part name [PRT0002]: <B>bracket &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

When you do this, the text in the titlebar of the main graphics window
changes to <I><B>**********Pro/ENGINEER Part: BRACKET**********</B></I>,
signifying that this is now the name of the current part in the active
window.  Since Pro/ENGINEER can have several parts, assemblies and
drawings open simultaneously in multiple windows, the asterisks are used
to indicate the currently active window.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="datums">DATUM PLANES (the first feature):</A></H3>

For this bracket (and all remaining parts in this set of exercises), you
will begin by creating a set of default <EM>datum planes</EM>.  These
are reference planes for use in defining all later geometry of the part.
They are not solid objects, and they won't show up in shaded images of
the part -- think of them as representing invisible, infinite planes.<P>

From the PART menu, select 
<P><B>Feature -&gt; Create -&gt; Datum -&gt; Plane -&gt; Default</B><P>

A set of three datum planes will appear on the screen.  Study the 
arrangement of these planes for a moment.  The following images may
help you see how the planes are positioned in relation to each other.
The image on the right shows the planes as if they were opaque.
<P>
<IMG SRC="datum_planes.gif"><P>

Note that datum planes are usually created singly <EM>except</EM>
where default datum planes are the first feature created in the part.
The three you see on the screen are actually three separate features.<P>

Datum planes in Pro/ENGINEER have two sides: a <EM>front side</EM>
and a <EM>rear side</EM>.  The front side of a datum plane is always
shown with a yellow border, whereas the rear side is shown with a red
border.  Clearly, you are looking at the front side of all three planes.
Arrows have been added to the figures above to indicate the directions in
which the front sides of the three datum planes are considered to face.
These directions are the outward normals to each plane.<P>

The following image illustrates the way front and rear sides of a datum
plane face in opposite directions ...
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="datum_plane_back.gif"><P>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feat_angle">EXTRUDED ANGLE SECTION:</A></H3>

You are now ready to create the first solid feature of the Bracket.  This
is generally chosen to be the major solid block from which the part will
be formed, and it should not contain too much geometrical detail.  For
the bracket, we will create this feature as a sharp-sided L-shaped
<EM>extruded protrusion</EM> (or extrusion, for short).  Pro/ENGINEER
uses the word `protrusion' to refer to a generalised blob of material.<P>

An extrusion is defined by
<UL>
<LI>first defining a sketching plane, then 
<LI>sketching the cross-sectional shape, and then
<LI>specifying how far this cross-section is to be extruded out from the
    plane in which the sketch has been made.
</UL>
<EM>By default, extrusions are always made towards the viewer</EM>
(i.e. out of the screen, when looking straight at the sketching plane).<P>

A general note may be helpful here concerning Pro/ENGINEER's default
menu selections.  Command menus will often appear on the screen with 
certain options already highlighted in red.  These are the default values,
and if they are suitable to you they do not need to be clicked again with
the mouse pointer (although that does no harm).  They can, of course, be
over-ridden by selecting different options on the menu, and they can be
re-selected if you change your mind.  In these notes, all the selections
required for building a given command string will be listed (both the 
defaults and those options which need to be actually clicked).<P>

From the FEAT menu, select
<P><B>Create -&gt; Solid | Protrusion -&gt; Extrude | Solid | Done -&gt; Single | Done -&gt; One Side | Blind | Done</B><P>

At this point you must define your sketching plane, so that Pro/ENGINEER
knows where to use your cross-sectional information.  You should see the
PRE_SKETCH and SETUP_PLANE and GET_SELECT menus on the screen (under the
MAIN menu, which is always present), and you are being requested to 
pick a sketching plane (... check the text in the message window). 
Using the LEFT mouse button, pick on DTM1 (datum plane no. 1) in the 
main graphics window, either by picking on its name or border.<P>

Notice the temporary arrow which now appears pointing out from DTM1, and read
the prompt in the Message Window.  Since the proposed direction of feature
creation is satisfactory, select <B>Okay</B> from the DIRECTION menu.<P>

There is one more step to take before you can start sketching.  Having
selected DTM1 as your sketching plane, you need to tell Pro/ENGINEER how to
orient this sketching plane on the screen (i.e. tell it `which way is up').
To do this, you must identify a plane that will be used as a horizontal or
vertical reference in the sketch view.  Such a reference plane must always
be perpendicular to the sketching plane.  In this case, since DTM1 will be
facing directly out from the screen, we could specify either that
<UL>
<LI>datum plane DTM2 shall face towards the <I>top</I> of the screen, or
<LI>datum plane DTM3 shall face towards the <I>left</I> of the screen,
</UL>
both of which are equivalent specifications.  From the SKET VIEW menu, select:
<P><B>Top</B><P>
and pick DTM2 (pick on its name or border using the LEFT mouse button).
This means that the yellow side of DTM2 will face towards the top of the
screen in the sketch view, and therefore that DTM2 will be the horizontal
reference for the section you are about to sketch.  In most cases it is best
to use one of the original three datum planes for this kind of reference.<P>

You have now given Pro/ENGINEER enough information to define a sketching
plane, so it presents you with the sketch view looking like this:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="sketch_view_blank.gif"><P>

Your view will also have a grid of faint lines to aid sketching.
Notice the yellow and red sides of the `edge-on' planes DTM2 and DTM3.
Are they facing the directions you expected them to ?<P>

You will have been placed automatically into the
<B>Sketcher -&gt; Mouse Sketch</B> mode, so you can immediately start
sketching.  Using the LEFT mouse buttons (to create lines), sketch the
cross section exactly as shown below (the small numbers are intended as
a guide to your sequence of points).  Use the MIDDLE mouse button to
end line creation.  Be careful not to create tiny little line segments
accidentally, as these will cause problems when you try to dimension and
regenerate the sketch later.  If you do create such problem lines, try
to delete them using the <B>Delete -&gt; Delete Many -&gt; Pick Many</B>
options.

<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="angle_sectn.gif"><P>

Now you must dimension your sketch.  Four dimensions are required to
define the shape of this section (i.e. the overall length, the overall
height, and the thicknesses of the vertical and horizontal arms).
Select <B>Dimension</B> from the SKETCHER menu.  Creation of the first
dimension is described in the following diagram. Create all four dimensions
in a similar fashion.
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="angle_dim_first.gif"><P>

Finally you must align the section to the existing part (i.e. to the
existing datum planes).  Pro/ENGINEER needs to be told that you want the
right-most vertical line aligned with datum DTM3, and the lower horizontal
line aligned with datum DTM2.  Select <B>Alignment</B> from the SKETCHER
menu.  Then click once on the right-most vertical line and once on DTM3.
The message window should confirm that the two entities have been
`-- ALIGNED --'.  Similarly click once on the lower horizontal line and 
once on DTM2 to align them.<P>

You have given Pro/ENGINEER all the information needed for it to reconstruct
the section, so select <B>Regenerate</B> from the SKETCHER menu.  If all 
goes well, you will see an encouraging confirmation in the message window.
Furthermore Pro/ENGINEER will assign a value to each of the symbolic
dimensions, and place you immediately into <B>Modify</B> mode so that you
can adjust the dimensions as desired.<P>

Specify the following dimensions:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="angle_dim_all.gif"><P>
and select <B>Regenerate | Done</B> from the SKETCHER menu.  The cross
section is now complete, and you are being prompted to enter an extrusion
depth.  The desired value in this case is 300mm.

<P><KBD>Enter depth [216.51]: <B>300 &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

Congratulations!  Your part now contains four features, namely the 3
datum planes and a (new) extruded protrusion.  To obtain an isometric,
shaded view, select:<P>
<B>View -&gt; Orientation -&gt; Default</B><P>
and then:<P>
<B>View -&gt; Cosmetic -&gt; Shade -&gt; Display</B>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="saving">SAVING YOUR WORK:</A></H3>

This is a good time to save your bracket model.  From the MAIN menu, select:
<P><B>Dbms -&gt; Save</B><P>
... and type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> (i.e. the [RETURN] key) to accept the
default object being offered for saving (see the prompt in the message
window).  Pro/ENGINEER confirms that the model has been stored to a file.
If you were to check the contents of your current working directory, you
would find that there is a new file there called <KBD>bracket.prt.1</KBD>
 -- the `<KBD>prt</KBD>' extension indicates that it is a <EM>part</EM> file,
and the `<KBD>.1</KBD>' suffix is a file version number.  Pro/ENGINEER
keeps all file versions unless explicitly instructed to delete out-dated
ones, so next time you save your part you will have two part files in the
directory (<KBD>bracket.prt.1</KBD> and <KBD>bracket.prt.2</KBD>), and so on.
This is generally a good thing, except that it generates large numbers of
files which can fill up the disk unless you occasionally purge them.
For the moment, go ahead and  save your model whenever you get to a useful
new stage in its development, and we will discuss purging later.<P>

It is also worth knowing that Pro/ENGINEER not only stores models on file,
it also lets them hang around in memory.  To demonstrate this, select 
<B>Quit Window</B> from the MAIN menu.  (Go on!  It's safe -- you just stored
it, didn't you?)  Now we will retrieve the part, not from disk, but from
Pro/ENGINEER's program memory.  From the MODE menu, select:<P>
<B>Part -&gt; Search/Retr</B><P>
The <B>Search/Retr</B> option is very useful, since it means you don't have
to remember any filenames or do any typing.  Notice that there are two
options in the lower half of the SELECT FILE menu:
<UL>
<LI><B>Current Dir</B> is the default, and searches the current directory;
<LI><B>In Session</B> searches program memory for every relevant object
    you have worked with in the current Pro/ENGINEER session.
</UL>

Select <B>In Session -&gt; BRACKET.PRT</B><P>
... and you should be back where you were a few minutes earlier.  Notice
that the cylinder part (PRT0001.PRT) was also available, even though you
quit that window ages ago.<P>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feat_rounds">ROUNDED EDGES:</A></H3>

You will now put some rounded fillets on three edges of the extrusion,
to make it look more like a real piece of angle section.  This is easily
achieved with the Pro/ENGINEER `Round' feature.<P>

Starting from the PART menu, select the following command string.<P>

<B>Feature -&gt; Create -&gt; Solid -&gt; Round -&gt; Edge | Constant |
Circular | No End Srf | Done</B><P>

You are now prompted to `<KBD>Specify edges to be
rounded/filleted</KBD>' by picking edges from the graphics window with
the LEFT mouse button.  Pick the edges shown highlighted in blue in the
next diagram, and then select <B>Done</B> from below the EDGE SEL menu.
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="edge_sel.gif"><P>

When prompted to specify a radius value option from the RADIUS
VAL menu, select <B>Enter</B> from that menu, and respond to the prompt
for a radius in the message window as follows:<P>
<KBD>Enter RADIUS [0.7500]: <B>8</B></KBD><P>

The fillets now appear.  Shade the image to see them better, i.e. select:<P>
<B>View -&gt; Cosmetic -&gt; Shade -&gt; Display</B><P>

Note that although there are three fillets, they all belong to only one
feature in your part.  They could have been created separately, but there
was no advantage in doing this, since they all had essentially the same
specification.  We could call this a `compound' feature.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feat_slot_hole">A SLOT AND A HOLE:</A></H3>

It is generally best not to work on a shaded image of a part when creating or
modifying features, so select <B>View -&gt; Regen View</B> to return to the
`Hidden Line' representation of your bracket. These instructions will also
assume that you are viewing the part in its default orientation.<P>

You will now create a slot and a hole in the 80mm-wide leg of the angle
section.  This will be another compound feature, since the hole and slot
will be created as a single <EM>cut</EM> feature (although they could
just as well be created separately).  Just as a protrusion is the most
general kind of `material addition' feature in Pro/ENGINEER, a cut is the
most general kind of `material removal' feature (much more general and
powerful, for example, than either the <EM>hole</EM> feature or the
<EM>slot</EM> feature of Pro/ENGINEER, which are almost never used).<P>

Similarly to the extrusion, a cut is defined by
<UL>
<LI>first defining a sketching plane, then
<LI>sketching the cross-sectional shape, and then
<LI>specifying how far this cross-section is to be extruded inwards
    (as if using a biscuit cutter) from the plane in which the sketch has
    been made.
</UL>
<EM>By default, cuts are always made away from the viewer</EM>
(i.e. into the screen, when looking straight at the sketching plane).
This is more-or-less the opposite to the case for an extrusion.<P>

<B>Feature -&gt; Create -&gt; Solid -&gt; Cut -&gt; Extrude | Solid |
Done -&gt; Single | Done -&gt; One Side | Thru All | Done</B><P>

Let's say we want to define the shape of the hole and slot by sketching
a cross-section on the <EM>underside</EM> of the part.  Now when you are
prompted to pick (or create) a sketching plane, an interesting problem
arises -- how do you point to regions of your model which lie behind
solid material?  We would like to be able to point to the underside of
the part without having to spin the view.  This is the sort of situation
where Pro/ENGINEER's `query select' facility comes in useful.  Select:
<P><B>Query Sel</B><P>
from the GET SELECT menu, and note the comment in the message window.

Pick a point on the screen directly on the (underside of) the longer leg
of the part.  Because the top surface of this part is the first solid
surface encountered by Pro/ENGINEER when it looks where you have picked,
it highlights the upper face (which is not the one you want).  But
notice that a CONFIRM menu has appeared under the GET SELECT menu, so 
that you can tell Pro/ENGINEER to continue looking for items `below the
surface'.  Select <B>Next</B> from the CONFIRM menu, and the next item
highlighted in red on the graphics window should be the one you want --
the underside of the part.  Select <B>Accept</B> from the CONFIRM menu.<P>

An arrow appears indicating a proposed direction for the creation of the
cut (i.e. upwards from the underside of the part into solid material).
This direction is fine, so select <B>Okay</B>.  Note that when you enter
sketcher mode, you will be looking in the direction of creation of the
cut (i.e. you will be looking directly at the lower surface of the part).<P>

When prompted to pick a horizontal or vertical reference plane for
sketching, ensure that <B>Bottom</B> is highlighted in the SKET VIEW menu,
and pick DTM3.  This means that the yellow side of datum plane 3 will be
made to face the bottom of the screen in sketch view.  As soon as you
do this, Pro/ENGINEER will take you into sketcher mode.  If you have 
carefully followed instructions, the screen will look like this: 
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch1.gif"><P>

There are many ways to sketch a slot efficiently -- here is just one
suggestion.  Begin by mouse-sketching a horizontal line near the right-hand
end of your view of the part.  Then, from the GEOMETRY menu, select 
<B>Line -&gt; Centreline</B>, and sketch a horizontal centreline a little
below your first line.  The result should look like this:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch2.gif"><P>

Now select <B>Mouse Sketch</B> again, and use the RIGHT mouse button
carefully to draw two tangent arcs from the ends of the first line. 
Try to locate the centres of these arcs on the centreline, as shown: 
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch3.gif"><P>

Although your section is not yet complete, it is useful to partially
dimension and regenerate it, so that the geometrical constraints can be
`locked-in'.  This helps prevent a section becoming too confused and
complex.  Select <B>Dimension</B> again, and see if you can achieve
a regenerated sketch looking like the following:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch4.gif"><P>

Now, starting from the SKETCHER menu, select <B>Geom Tools -&gt; Mirror</B>
and in response to the prompt, pick the centreline you have already drawn.
You want to mirror all the entities in your sketch about this centreline, 
so select <B>All | Done</B> from the MIRROR menu.  Bingo!  You now have
a sketch of the full slot.  However, the dimensioning is a bit unorthodox
(slots are usually dimensioned across their full width), so delete the
11mm half-width dimension, and replace it with a new dimension between the
upper and lower horizontal lines.  Regenerate to obtain the following result:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch5.gif"><P>

Finally let us not forget the hole at the other end of the part.  We want
this hole to be on the same horizontal centreline as the slot.  If you
locate the circle carefully in your sketch, Pro/ENGINEER will `realise'
this, and automatically align it with the slot's centreline.
Select <B>Mouse Sketch</B> again, and use the MIDDLE mouse button to
sketch a circle of roughly the right diameter and in the desired location.
Dimension the circle so that, when regenerated, the overall sketch looks
like the following diagram:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="slot_sketch6.gif"><P>

When you select <B>Done</B> from the SKETCHER menu, Pro/ENGINEER asks you
whether to remove material from inside or outside the sketched regions.
A red arrow appears on the sketch to help you make this decision.
In this case, the proposed direction is not what you want, so select 
<B>Flip</B> from the DIRECTION menu.  Now when you select <B>Okay</B> 
from the DIRECTION menu, your slot and hole will be created!  To see this,
view the part in its default orientation again.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feat_sweep">A SWEPT HANDLE:</A></H3>

The `handle' of your bracket may be defined in terms of the volume swept
by a (circular) cross-section as it travels along (and remains normal to)
a curving path in space.  The path is called a <EM>trajectory</EM>, and
in this case it is planar.  More generally, the trajectory may follow a
3-dimensional curve, and the swept cross-section can have any planar shape.
The name for this kind of feature in Pro/ENGINEER is a <EM>sweep</EM>.<P>

The sequence of operations for creating a sweep is:
<UL>
<LI>define the trajectory;
<LI>define the cross-section.
</UL>

In this case, the trajectory lies in a plane which is different from any
existing datum plane, so the sketching plane will itself need to be
created.  This datum plane could be created as a distinct self-contained
feature.  However, because the swept handle is the only feature which will
make reference to this sketching plane, we will choose instead to create the
datum plane <EM>on the fly</EM>, as a `sub-feature' of the sweep feature.<P>

From the PART menu, select:<P>

<B>Feature -&gt; Create -&gt; Solid | Protrusion -&gt; Sweep | Solid
| Done -&gt; Sketch Traj | Done</B><P>

Then from the SETUP PLANE menu, select <B>Make Datum</B><P>

You then need to provide sufficient information to Pro/ENGINEER in order
to <EM>constrain</EM> the new datum plane.  In this case the task is
easy since you merely need to specify an offset plane, and so will need
only one constraint.<P>

From the DATUM PLANE menu, select: <B>Offset</B>, and then pick DTM2
on the graphics screen, and select <B>Enter Value</B> from the OFFSET menu.
Notice that a small green vector has appeared on the graphics window
defining a direction normal to DTM2, and that you are being prompted to
enter data in the message window.  Respond as follows:<P>

<KBD>Enter offset in the indicated direction, &lt;ESC&gt; to quit [7.86]:
<B>25 &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

The new datum plane is fully defined, so select <B>Done</B> as prompted.
To avoid ambiguity, Pro/ENGINEER now requires you to select the direction
for viewing the sketching plane.  Believe it or not, there is a small red
vector lurking somewhere on the screen, defining a direction normal to
DTM4.  The proposed direction is fine, so select <B>Okay</B>.  Finally you
must now specify the orientation of the sketching plane by nominating the
by-now-familiar horizontal or vertical reference plane.  (Try to predict
how the sketch plane will appear if you carry out the following step.)
Ensure that <B>Bottom</B> is highlighted in the SKET VIEW menu, and pick
datum plane DTM3 so that its yellow side will face down towards the
bottom of the sketch view screen.  (Was your prediction correct?)<P>

Begin your sketch of the trajectory with the three lines illustrated in
this diagram:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="handle_sketch1.gif"><P>

Next select (beginning from the SKETCHER menu) 
<B>Sketch -&gt; Arc -&gt; Fillet</B>, and pick first the left-hand
vertical sketched line (roughly halfway up the line), and then the
horizontal sketched line.  A fillet arc should appear.  Repeat this
process on the right-hand vertical line to obtain a second fillet.
Select <B>Alignment</B>, and align the lower end of each of the vertical
lines with DTM3.  Then add dimensions to achieve a regenerated sketch
like the one shown below:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="handle_sketch2.gif"><P>

Notice that Pro/ENGINEER puts a cyan vector at one end of the sketched 
trajectory to indicate the start point.  It is important to be aware of
this starting point and its corresponding vector, because when you come
to sketch the cross-section in a few moments' time, you will be `looking
along' this vector (i.e. the cross-sectional sketching plane will be
perpendicular to the trajectory's starting vector).<P>

Finalise the trajectory by regenerating and selecting <B>Done</B>.
When you then select an option from the SWEEP_OPT2 menu (select
<B>Free Ends | Done</B> ), Pro/ENGINEER will immediately present you
with another sketch view -- this time for sketching the cross-section.
As expected, the view is facing in the same direction as the starting
vector of the trajectory.  If you look carefully, you will see that there
is a pair of cyan cross-hairs marking the location of the starting vector.
(The vector itself can't be seen, because you are viewing it `end-on'.)
Your sketch view should look like this:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="handle_sketch3.gif"><P>

You are now ready to sketch the cross-section of the sweeep.  This is just
a circle, centred on the cross-hairs.  Ensure that <B>Mouse Sketch</B> is
selected in the GEOMETRY menu, and sketch your circle (recall that you use
the MIDDLE mouse button for mouse-sketching circles).  When you dimension
and regenerate the circle in the usual fashion, (modifying its dimensions
and regenerating again), the result should be:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="handle_sketch4.gif"><P>

To finish the sweep feature, select <B>Done</B> from below the SKETCHER
menu.  You can see it in all its glory by viewing it in default orientation.
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="handle.gif"><P>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feat_welds">WELD FILLETS:</A></H3>

Your bracket is almost complete.  The final task is to place a `round' on
the two circular edges where the new handle joins the rest of the part.
From the FEAT menu, select:<P>

<B>Create -&gt; Solid -&gt; Round -&gt; Edge | Constant |
Circular | No End Srf | Done</B><P>

You are now prompted to `<KBD>Specify edges to be rounded/filleted.</KBD>'
The edges you want to fillet are hidden by the short leg of the 
angle-section, so you must use `query select' to pick them.  Select
<B>Query Sel</B> and pick on one of the (hidden) edges.  When the desired
edge highlights in dark blue, check the statement in the message window,
and confirm by selecting <B>Accept</B>.<P>

Note that only half of the intersecting edge is highlighted.  This is
because Pro/ENGINEER represents complete cylinders as two equal halves,
so that the edges become two 180 degree arcs rather than one complete
circle.  When you are rounding the edges of cylinders, however, you only
need to select one of these edges.  The round will automatically wrap
around the entire cylinder.<P>

Pro/ENGINEER stays in `query select' mode, so you simply repeat the
process for the hidden edge at the other end of the handle.  When both
edges are highlighted, select <B>Done</B> from below the EDGE SEL menu,
and select <B>Enter</B> from the RADIUS VAL menu.  The the desired fillet
radius (6mm) as follows:<P>
<KBD>Enter RADIUS [0.8100]: <B>6</B></KBD><P>

The fillets now appear.  Well done!  You have finished modelling your first
real part in Pro/ENGINEER.  This may have seemed painful, but you have
in fact come an amazingly long way down the path of learning how to use
this software package.<P>

When you spin the image appropriately, and shade it, your bracket should
now look just like the one at the start of this document.  Check it out.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="purging">PURGING YOUR WORK:</A></H3>

If you have been saving your work regularly after each new feature is
added, you will now have many versions of the file <EM>bracket.prt</EM>
in your directory.  You can check the contents of the current directory
from within Pro/ENGINEER by selecting (from the MAIN menu)
<B>Misc -&gt; List Dir</B> and typing a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> to accept the 
default directory being proposed in the message window.  Do it now ...<P>

For this exercise, you have no need of the out-dated versions of your
bracket.  To remove all except the latest version, select (again from
the MAIN menu) <B>Dbms -&gt; Purge</B> and type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B>
to accept the default object being proposed in the message window.  Now 
if you list the contents of the current directory again, you
will see that all but the latest versions of <EM>bracket.prt</EM> have
been removed.<P>

It's a good idea to purge your models occasionally, since the old file
versions take up valuable disk space.  Purging is a handy way to avoid
exceeding your storage quota (a system issue, not directly related to
Pro/ENGINEER).

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="questions">REVIEW QUESTIONS (*** for assessment ***):</A></H3>

Try answering the following questions.  Write the answers on a sheet of
A4 paper (make sure it has your name and your tutor's name at the top).

<OL>
<LI>How many features does your `bracket' part contain?  List them.
<LI>Which features are the <EM>parents</EM> of the welded fillets which
    you added right at the end?  (Roughly speaking, the `parent features'
    of a given `child feature' are those features which are used as
    a reference for defining the child.)
</OL>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<HR>
<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
