<HEAD>
<TITLE>Exercise GE1: GEOMETRIC MODELLING -- HEAD OF A LEGO(tm) PERSON</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<H1>Exercise GE1 (cont.): ... LEGO(tm) HEAD</H1>

<!-- next filename.gif should have same stem as present filename.html -->
<IMG SRC="head.gif">
<HR>
<!-- next nextfile.html must match next file in series -->
<A HREF="lego_torso.html"><IMG SRC="skip.gif"></A><P>

<H2><A NAME="start">Contents (`HEAD of a LEGO person'):</A></H2>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#started">GETTING STARTED</A>
<LI><A HREF="#oview">OVERVIEW OF THIS PART (the head)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#feats_outline">BRIEF OUTLINE OF FEATURES FOR `head'</A>
	<UL>
	<LI><A HREF="#datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#revolved_protrusion">A Revolved Protrusion</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#two_rounds">Rounds on the upper and lower edges</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#bottom_hole">A large hole (Extruded Cut) in the base</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#top_hole">A small hole (Coaxial Hole) in the top</A>
	</UL>
<LI><A HREF="#submit">SUBMITTING THIS PART FOR ASSESSMENT</A>
</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="started">GETTING STARTED:</A></H3>

Before you begin this new part, ensure that you have saved any previous work
in the current Pro/ENGINEER session (by selecting <B>Dbms -&gt; Save</B>
from the MAIN menu, and typing a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> to accept the proposed
name).  This might also be a good time to get rid of all the out-dated 
versions of the part you have just finished, so that disk space is not wasted.  
If that part is still current, just select <B>Dbms -&gt; Purge</B> from the
MAIN menu, and type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> to accept the default.  The
<B>Purge</B> command is quite safe -- it leaves you with only the latest
version of your part file.<P>

If the previous part you were working on is to be submitted for
assessment, you should also save a copy of it to your special `submission'
directory by selecting <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B> and typing in the full
pathname of your submission directory (refer to the handout sheet entitled 
<EM>Assessment of Work in Exercise GE1</EM> for more complete instructions
on how to do this).<P>

Then clear the graphics window by selecting <B>Quit Window</B> from the 
MAIN menu.  The MODE menu should appear beneath the MAIN menu.<P>

Start modelling your new part by selecting <B>Part</B> from the MODE menu.
Select <B>Create</B> from the ENTERPART menu, and give your part a name:
<P><KBD>Enter Part name [PRT0001]: <B>head &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="oview">OVERVIEW OF THIS PART (the head):</A></H3>

Broadly speaking, the head of the LEGO person may be regarded as a simple
<EM>solid of revolution</EM>.  (This is certainly true if we ignore the
complication of the tiny `tri-star' inside its upper hole -- and it is
recommended that you ignore the tri-star for the purpose of this exercise.)
It is possible to create the head in Pro/ENGINEER with a single feature,
however to do so would be to break the cardinal rule of feature-based
modelling: <EM>`keep your features simple'</EM>.  Much better to have a
larger number of simple features, than a few very cumbersome features which
are difficult to sketch and modify.<P>

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feats_outline">BRIEF OUTLINE OF FEATURES FOR `head':</A></H3>

There are many ways to model the `head' part.  One suggested approach is
to use the following set of features:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes</A>
<LI><A HREF="#revolved_protrusion">A Revolved Protrusion</A>
<LI><A HREF="#two_rounds">Rounds on the upper and lower edges</A>
<LI><A HREF="#bottom_hole">A large hole (Extruded Cut) in the base</A>
<LI><A HREF="#top_hole">A small hole (Coaxial Hole) in the top</A>
</UL>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes:</A></H4>
For any part of consequence, <EM>always</EM> begin by creating a set of
datum planes.  These can be used to reference other features, and can be
helpful for defining planes of symmetry.  It is generally better to use
datum planes in dimensioning and aligning your model, than to use the 
surfaces of solid features.  Using datum planes as references minimises
the risk of setting up unnecessary parent/child relationships between
features.<P>

Even though the head is such a simple axisymmetric part, it is still 
worthwhile starting with a set of datum planes.  If at some later stage 
you want to add a non-axisymmetric feature to the head (a face, say, or
perhaps the tri-star in the upper hole), then this will be much simpler
if a set of datum planes is already defined.<P>

You should remember how to do this.  Select:<P>
<B>Feature -&gt; Create -&gt; Datum -&gt; Plane -&gt; Default</B>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="revolved_protrusion">A Revolved Protrusion:</A></H4>
Most of the solid part of the head can be made with a single revolved
protrusion.  The three main cylindrical diameters can be incorporated
into this one feature.  You will need to examine the menu options and 
message text carefully on the screen in order to implement the following
instructions -- they will be expressed much less formally than before.<P>

From the FEAT menu, create a solid protrusion with a revolved form.
Choose the 360 degree option.  Accept the default values for other options.
Pick DTM1 as the sketching plane, accept the proposed viewing direction, 
and pick DTM2 to face the <B>Top</B> when choosing a horizontal reference
plane for orienting the sketching view.<P>

In the sketcher, sketch a closed section something like the one below:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="head_sec1.gif"><P>

The sketch contains one (vertical) centreline and eight ordinary lines.
Align the centreline to DTM3, and the lowest horizontal line to DTM2.
Add symbolic dimensions to the sketch until you think it is dimensioned
adequately, and then try to regenerate it.  If regeneration is not
successful, continue to add/delete dimensions, or align the sketch to the
datum planes, until the sketch does regenerate.  Then modify the values of
your sketch dimensions according to your measurements on a real LEGO head.
Regenerate the sketch after modification, and select <B>Done</B> when you
are satisfied with your section.  The revolved solid feature appears
immediately.  Save your part to protect your investment!

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="two_rounds">Rounds on the upper and lower edges:</A></H4>
Create a `round' on the upper and lower edges of the largest of the three
cylinders on your previous (revolved) feature.  Be aware that these rounds
on a real LEGO head have slightly different dimensions.  You can deal with
this either by placing two separate round features, each using the (default)
<B>Constant</B> option, or by creating a single <B>MultiConst</B> feature
which allows you to enter different radii for each edge selected.<P>

Note that you must select <B>Enter</B> from the RADIUS VAL menu in order
to enable entry of the radius values from the keyboard.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="bottom_hole">A large hole (Extruded Cut) in the base:</A></H4>
The most general way to remove material in Pro/ENGINEER is to use a `cut'.
We will use a cut here to make the large hole in the underside of the head,
even though a `hole' feature would serve just as well.<P>

Create a single solid extruded cut.  The cut will be `blind' (i.e. of a
specified depth), and extrude from one side of the sketching plane.
The intention is that you are going to sketch the circular cross-section of 
the hole, so when you are prompted to pick a sketching plane, which plane
are you going to choose?  Think about it, and give it a go ...  (you will
need to pick a second plane as a reference to help orient your sketch).<P>

Sketch, align, dimension, regenerate, modify, and regenerate your sketch
again until you are satisfied.  When you are done, type in the required
depth for the blind extrusion.  View and save your part.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="top_hole">A small hole (Coaxial Hole) in the top:</A></H4>
Just for variety, we will create the small hole through the top of the
head as a `coaxial hole'.  This is convenient, because the creation of the
previous feature (the large hole in the base) should have left us with
an axis with which to align the present hole.  It should be possible to
perform this entire hole creation while viewing the part in its default view,
so select the default view now.<P>

Create a solid hole feature.  It is to be a single, <B>Coaxial</B> hole,
which will extend through all geometry on one side of the selected surface.
Type in the required diameter, pick the axis for the hole, and pick the
surface in which the hole is to be made.  Your head part is now finished.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="submit">SUBMITTING THIS PART FOR ASSESSMENT:</A></H3>

When you have modelled your `head' part as far as you intend, you should
submit it for assessment by your tutor.  To do this, you must save a copy
of it to the special directory which has been set up for you in the common
area of the computer's filesystem.  This directory has the same name as your
login name.  For example, if your login name is `jsmith', then you must save
the part to the directory named <KBD>/home/common/me/ge1/jsmith</KBD>.<P>

If you have finished your `head' part for the time being, submit it for
assessment now by following these instructions (you can always re-submit
it again later if you improve your part).  Beginning from the MAIN menu,
select <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B>.  You will be prompted for the name of a
directory into which Pro/ENGINEER will save a copy of your part (the
default offered will be your current working directory).  In response to
the prompt, type:
<P><KBD>Which directory ? [...]: <B>/home/common/me/ge1/</B></KBD><I>yourname</I><KBD><B> &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>
... of course replacing `<I>yourname</I>' with your own login name.<P>

Ensure that the object to be saved is the `head' (it should be the default
offered in the message window -- if so, then just type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B>
at the prompt).  You will see a reassuring comment if Pro/ENGINEER can
successfully store your part in the desired location.  If not, then please
<EM>consult your tutor</EM>.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<HR>
