<HEAD>
<TITLE>Exercise GE1: GEOMETRIC MODELLING -- TORSO OF A LEGO(tm) PERSON</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<H1>Exercise GE1 (cont.): ... LEGO(tm) TORSO</H1>

<!-- next filename.gif should have same stem as present filename.html -->
<IMG SRC="torso.gif">
<HR>
<!-- next nextfile.html must match next file in series -->
<A HREF="lego_hips.html"><IMG SRC="skip.gif"></A><P>

<H2><A NAME="start">Contents (`TORSO of a LEGO person'):</A></H2>
<OL>
<LI><A HREF="#started">GETTING STARTED</A>
<LI><A HREF="#oview">OVERVIEW OF THIS PART (the torso)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#feats_outline">BRIEF OUTLINE OF FEATURES FOR `torso'</A>
	<UL>
	<LI><A HREF="#datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#main_extrusion">A main trapezoidal block (Extrusion)</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#neck_cylinder">A cylindrical neck (Extrusion)</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#shell">A hollow outer Shell</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#arm_holes">A pair of arm holes (Extruded Cut)</A>
	<LI><A HREF="#edge_rounds">Rounds on the outer edges</A>
	</UL>
<LI><A HREF="#submit">SUBMITTING THIS PART FOR ASSESSMENT</A>
</OL>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="started">GETTING STARTED:</A></H3>

Before you begin this new part, ensure that you have saved any previous work
in the current Pro/ENGINEER session (by selecting <B>Dbms -&gt; Save</B>
from the MAIN menu, and typing a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> to accept the proposed
name).  This might also be a good time to get rid of all the out-dated 
versions of the part you have just finished, so that disk space is not wasted.  
If that part is still current, just select <B>Dbms -&gt; Purge</B> from the
MAIN menu, and type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B> to accept the default.  The
<B>Purge</B> command is quite safe -- it leaves you with only the latest
version of your part file.<P>

If the previous part you were working on is to be submitted for
assessment, you should also save a copy of it to your special `submission'
directory by selecting <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B> and typing in the full
pathname of your submission directory (refer to the handout sheet entitled 
<EM>Assessment of Work in Exercise GE1</EM> for more complete instructions
on how to do this).<P>

Then clear the graphics window by selecting <B>Quit Window</B> from the 
MAIN menu.  The MODE menu should appear beneath the MAIN menu.<P>

Start modelling your new part by selecting <B>Part</B> from the MODE menu.
Select <B>Create</B> from the ENTERPART menu, and give your part a name:
<P><KBD>Enter Part name [PRT0001]: <B>torso &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="oview">OVERVIEW OF THIS PART (the torso):</A></H3>

The torso of a LEGO person has two planes of symmetry, and we will make use
of these when modelling the part in Pro/ENGINEER.  It is also helpful to
regard the torso as a solid block which has been `hollowed out' to leave an
outer shell of more-or-less constant shell thickness.  Observant students
will notice that even the cylindrical `neck' on top of the torso has been
hollowed out in this way.  Again, we will make use of this `shelled' 
characteristic when creating the Pro/ENGINEER model.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="feats_outline">BRIEF OUTLINE OF FEATURES FOR `torso':</A></H3>

There are many ways to model the `torso' part.  One suggested approach is
to use the following set of features:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes</A>
<LI><A HREF="#main_extrusion">A main trapezoidal block (Extrusion)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#neck_cylinder">A cylindrical neck (Extrusion)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#shell">A hollow outer Shell</A>
<LI><A HREF="#arm_holes">A pair of arm holes (Extruded Cut)</A>
<LI><A HREF="#edge_rounds">Rounds on the outer edges</A>
</UL>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="datum_planes">A default set of Datum Planes:</A></H4>
As usual, begin by creating a default set of three datum planes.  Note that
these instructions will aim to apply a consistent orientation to these planes
in relation to the LEGO person.  In general, <EM>datum plane DTM1 will be
used as the vertical mid-plane which bisects the right side of the LEGO
person from its left side</EM>.  Furthermore, <EM>the front (yellow) side of
datum plane DTM3 will be taken as facing towards the front of the LEGO
person</EM>.  To help visualise and remember the orientation of these datum
planes, it might be helpful to make a sketch on paper of the default set of
datum planes as shown here, and keep the sketch handy.
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="dtm_planes.gif">

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="main_extrusion">A main trapezoidal block (Extrusion):</A></H4>
The default option for various kinds of solid features is for them to be
created on <B>One Side</B> of a sketching plane.  However, it is often useful
to extrude a solid (protrusion or cut) an equal distance on <B>Both Sides</B>
of a sketching plane.  This enables us to exploit planes of symmetry in a
part more effectively.<P>

From the FEAT menu, create a single solid protrusion with an extruded form.
As a suggestion, make the extrusion to extend from <B>Both Sides</B> of the
sketching plane.  This will force the feature to be symmetrical about the
sketching plane.<P>

Pick DTM3 to be the sketching plane, and accept the default viewing
direction.  Make DTM1 to be a vertical reference for orienting the
sketching view, such that it faces to the <B>Right</B> of the screen.
In the sketcher, sketch a closed section something like this:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="torso_sec1.gif"><P>

The above sketch illustrates a useful technique in Pro/ENGINEER:
<EM>exaggerate!</EM>  For example, there is no danger of the above sloping
lines being mistaken for vertical lines.  Exaggerated sketches help to create
unambiguous geometry for the Pro/ENGINEER Sketcher to solve.  Of course, once
the sketch is regenerated, the exact dimensions can be safely entered.<P>

Note that you will need to align your sketch to the existing datum planes
(for example, you might align the lower horizontal line with DTM2).  In the
example above, additional horizontal dimensions have been added to make the
section symmetrical about the vertical DTM1.  A more elegant sketching method
would be to sketch a vertical centreline to indicate this symmetry (aligning
the centreline with DTM1).  The additional dimensions (shown as `sd0' and
`sd2') would then be unnecessary.<P>

When you finally regenerate your section with the correct dimensions, select
<B>Done</B> and enter the overall extrusion depth to complete the extruded
solid feature.  Save the part.  Revert to the default view orientation.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="neck_cylinder">A cylindrical neck (Extrusion):</A></H4>

If the first solid feature was created on <B>Both Sides</B> of the sketching
plane, the result should look something like:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="torso_sec2.gif"><P>

You now want to create the cylindrical `neck' which projects from the top of
the torso.  This feature will be another extrusion just like the last, except
that it will be extruded on only one side of its sketching plane.  To begin,
pick the uppermost solid surface of the part to define the sketching plane
(i.e. the one highlighted here in red):
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="torso_sec3.gif"><P>

(Just for fun, see if you can predict how the sketching view will be oriented
before you pick the orientation reference.  Were you correct?)<P>

Go through the familiar sketching cycle:
<UL>
<LI>sketch the shape;
<LI>add symbolic dimensions (don't modify them yet);
<LI>align the section to the part;
<LI>attempt to regenerate, and add additional geometrical constraints
    (dimensions and alignments) if necessary;
<LI>continue in this manner until the sketch regenerates successfully;
<LI>then (and not before then!) modify dimensions to the desired values;
<LI>regenerate the sketch to incorporate the new dimensions;
<LI>select <B>Done</B> when the sketch is complete.
</UL>

Complete the feature by entering the desired extrusion distance.  The solid
cylinder is created towards you (i.e. out of the screen), as is always the
case for protrusions.  (Note: this is the opposite of `cut' features, which
are extruded away from the viewer, into the screen.)  Viewed again in its
default orientation, the part should now look like this:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="torso_neck.gif"><P>

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="shell">A hollow outer Shell:</A></H4>

The torso of a LEGO person is approximately a hollow shell with a constant
wall thickness.  Fortunately, Pro/ENGINEER has a very powerful feature-type,
called a <EM>shell</EM>, for exactly this kind of shape.  A shell feature in
Pro/ENGINEER is defined by specifying:
<UL>
<LI>the `entry surfaces' on an existing solid (these are the surfaces which
    will be partially removed to form an opening into the new hollow interior
    of the solid); and
<LI>the wall thickness.  A different thickness can be defined for each
    exterior surface of the shell, if desired.
</UL>

From the PART menu, create a solid <B>Shell</B> feature on the torso.  The
entry to the shell will be from underneath (i.e. through the lower surface,
as seen on the previous sketch), so use <B>Query Sel</B> to pick the hidden
underside of your part, and select <B>Done Sel</B> to signal that you only
want the one entry surface.  Enter the desired wall thickness when prompted.
It is recommended that you use a constant wall thickness throughout this
shell, so just decline the opportunity to specify different wall thicknesses
by selecting <B>Done</B> from the SHELL EXIT menu.  Presto!  The torso is
immediately hollowed out.<P>

Notice that the hollow shell extends up into the cylindrical `neck' of the
torso (provided that you chose a wall thickness less than the neck radius).
Check to see whether this is what happens inside the neck protrusion on a
real LEGO person.  Think about what might be different if the torso were to
be shelled out <EM>before</EM> the neck protrusion was added.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="arm_holes">A pair of arm holes (Extruded Cut):</A></H4>

The torso contains two round holes to which the arms may be attached.  These
holes are in fact perpendicular to the sloping sides of the torso, and are
therefore exactly round.  For the sake of this exercise, however, the holes 
may be approximated by extruding a cut <EM>horizontally</EM> on both sides of
the central plane of symmetry (datum plane DTM1).  Think about what shape of
hole such a horizontal cylindrical cut will make in the sloping sides of the
torso...  In this case, the sloping sides are sufficiently close to being
vertical for such distortion to be neglected.<P>

Create a single solid <B>Cut</B>, extruded <B>Through All</B> material on
<B>Both Sides</B> of the central sketching plane (datum plane DTM1).  The
sketch for this cut will be a simple circle, with its centrepoint aligned to
the edge-view of datum plane DTM3.  When the cut is completed, notice how it
leaves a horizontal datum axis (probably called A_2) which is visible in the
default orientation.  Most features with a circular cross-section (whether
holes, round cuts or round extrusions) will leave visible axes such as this.

<!-- . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . . -->
<H4><A NAME="edge_rounds">Rounds on the outer edges:</A></H4>

By now, your part will look something like:
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="torso_holes.gif"><P>

The next feature is optional, since (a) it is trivial to make, and (b) it
will substantially increase the size of your part file on disk.  However, it
will tend to give a `finished appearance' to your part.<P>

Create a single set of <B>Constant</B>-radius <B>Round</B> features on your
part.  The edges to be rounded should include the four edges of the upper
rectangle, and the four sloping edges.  The only difficulty will be picking
the edges which are `hidden' at the rear of your current view: you should use
<B>Query Sel</B> to pick those edges.  (HINT:  Always ensure you are viewing
a part in its default orientation when you are picking edges, as this avoids
ambiguity.  In fact, use the default orientation as much as possible.)<P>

Well done!  You have finished the LEGO person's torso.  Make sure you save
your part (select <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B> from the MAIN menu), and purge
the out-dated versions to save disk space (select <B>Dbms -&gt; Purge</B>,
again from the MAIN menu).

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<!------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<HR>
<H3><A NAME="submit">SUBMITTING THIS PART FOR ASSESSMENT:</A></H3>

When you have modelled your `torso' part as far as you intend, you should
submit it for assessment by your tutor.  To do this, you must save a copy
of it to the special directory which has been set up for you in the common
area of the computer's filesystem.  This directory has the same name as your
login name.  For example, if your login name is `jsmith', then you must save
the part to the directory named <KBD>/home/common/me/ge1/jsmith</KBD>.<P>

If you have finished your `torso' part for the time being, submit it for
assessment now by following these instructions (you can always re-submit
it again later if you improve your part).  Beginning from the MAIN menu,
select <B>Dbms -&gt; Backup</B>.  You will be prompted for the name of a
directory into which Pro/ENGINEER will save a copy of your part (the
default offered will be your current working directory).  In response to
the prompt, type:
<P><KBD>Which directory ? [...]: <B>/home/common/me/ge1/</B></KBD><I>yourname</I><KBD><B> &lt;CR&gt;</B></KBD><P>
... of course replacing `<I>yourname</I>' with your own login name.<P>

Ensure that the object to be saved is the `torso' (it should be the default
offered in the message window -- if so, then just type a <B>&lt;CR&gt;</B>
at the prompt).  You will see a reassuring comment if Pro/ENGINEER can
successfully store your part in the desired location.  If not, then please
<EM>consult your tutor</EM>.

<P><A HREF="#start">Return to Contents at the start of this document ? <IMG ALIGN=top SRC="back.gif"></A>

<HR>
