<html>
<head>
   <title>Research Proposal</title>
   <meta name="Author" content="">
   <meta name="GENERATOR" content="Mozilla/2.01Gold (Win32)">
</head>
<body>

<center><p><b><font SIZE=+2>RESEARCH PROPOSAL</font></b> </p></center>

<p><i>THESIS TITLE:</i> An Optimisation of Combustion Systems for Stirling
Engine Cogeneration Systems. </p>

<p><i>SUPERVISOR:</i> <a href="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/staff/academic/jkr.htm">Dr.
J.K. Raine</a> </p>

<p><b>INTRODUCTION </b></p>

<p>Stirling Cycle engines have been operating since the beginning of last
century, initially as an alternative to steam engines. It wasnt until
the late 1930s that the problems associated with the early engines and
the complex thermodynamics of this cycle started to be solved. This led
to a wide range of possible applications for the cycle including cryogenic
coolers, heat pumps, prime movers, and generators. The characteristics
of the cycle also suit it ideally for cogeneration applications. </p>

<p>The Stirling cycle uses external combustion therefore it is possible
to run the engine on a wide range of fuels and have a high degree of control
over the combustion processes. Similarly all the heat removed from the
engine is done externally. This is in contrast to an internal combustion
engine in which two thirds of the heat removed from the engine goes out
the exhaust. These two properties of the Stirling cycle make it a prime
candidate for cogeneration systems. For example the water circulating through
the cold end of a Stirling engine is essentially the same as a wet back
for a log fire which heats water for the hot water cylinder. Constant combustion
used in the Stirling cycle also enables high control of the heat source
ideally suited for Recuperation and Exhaust heat recovery. </p>

<p>Over the past five years the Mechanical Engineering department has been
engaged in the research of Stirling engine generators. Work done by Dr
Don Clucas lead to a prototype Stirling engine for charging 12 Volt batteries
on yachts. The previous research has concentrated on the design of the
internal workings of the Stirling cycle. This did not include detailed
design of the heat input devices to the engine and the utilisation of heat
removed from the cycle. </p>

<p>The aim of this project is to investigate and analyse the external inputs
and outputs of a Stirling engine generator system. Provision of heat to
the hot end heat exchangers and coolant to the cold end heat exchangers
are the external inputs to the cycle. The external outputs include the
use of exhaust gases for heating, the increase in coolant temperature and
the electrical output. As a result of this analysis an optimisation of
the variables will be undertaken to give an overall system that has minimum
fuel input to achieve the required electrical power output and maximum
waste heat utilisation. This will be applied to a scaled up version of
the prototype engine DM5 developed by Dr D. Clucas as part of his PhD and
it will have an electrical power output of approximately 3kW. This size
of engine fits the required output power for use as a remote area power
supply (RAPS) or for use in a domestic cogeneration application. </p>

<p><b>1. PROPOSED WORK</b></p>

<p><b>1.1 Literature Research</b></p>

<p>A comprehensive search of relevant literature has been and will continue
to be undertaken during the course of the project to ascertain the present
technology in the area of Stirling engine research. This field is large
and covers a wide range of disciplines with a large amount of literature
available, however there is only a small amount of information available
within this field on external systems for Stirling engines so it is necessary
to look at in the wider areas of burner design, combustion, recuperation
and cogeneration. After an initial search into current publications very
few publications were found on the application of overall combustion systems
for Stirling cycle engines. </p>

<p><b>1.2 3kW Engine Design</b></p>

<p>To conduct the research on the combustion system it is necessary to
have a test engine that is designed to incorporate the required control
and data acquisition equipment. As mentioned above a test engine with a
3kW electrical power output will be designed based on the research of Dr
D. Clucas. This size of engine was chosen as a result of studies into the
requirements for electricity generation within the domestic sector and
the possibility of more accurate measurements than the low power 200W engine
developed by Dr Clucas. This size of engine is also much more commercially
viable with a larger market potential. </p>

<p><b>1.3 Burner Configurations</b></p>

<p>LPG has been chosen as the fuel source for the heater to simplify the
analysis Future work could look into the application of different fuels
into the system design. This leaves four major variables to produce an
efficiency heat source for the Stirling engine: </p>

<ul>
<ul>
<ol>
<li>Burner type (Primary and/or secondary air combustion) </li>

<li>Blower, the need for forced aspiration for combustion. </li>

<li>Recuperation, using exhaust gases to preheat the incoming combustion
air. </li>

<li>Recovery of exhaust heat, for example using the exhaust gases to heat
water. </li>
</ol>
</ul>
</ul>

<p>Initially several possible configurations for the burner will be decided
upon and prototypes built for testing. The best prototype burner will be
refined and optimised using a computer based finite element analysis. The
design of the burner and the fins on the heat exchanges of the Stirling
engine are closely associated so the test engine must facilitate a variety
of heat exchanger designs. </p>

<p><b>1.4 Computer Modelling</b></p>

<p>Once the burner configuration has been decided upon a model of the entire
system will be developed, including the recuperation and hot water heating
variables. There are two possible applications for the computer model within
the scope of this project: </p>

<ul>
<ul>
<ol>
<li>Emphasise the experimental side by testing the system under varying
conditions and using a simplified analytical model to back up the test
results. </li>

<li>Emphasise the computational side by developing an extensive computational
model going into the intricate workings of the Stirling cycle to produce
an optimal system solution. The results would then be confirmed on the
test engine. </li>
</ol>
</ul>
</ul>

<p>The second option requires the use of high level computer software to
calculate the instantaneous conditions within the Stirling cycle. At present
we have a program, the Urieli &amp; Berchowitz model, which is becoming
obsolete and been questioned in its accuracy. It would be highly preferable
to obtain a modern computer program such as GLIMPS or one of its derivative
to do this work for us but these programs are costly. </p>

<p><b>1.5 Optimisation</b></p>

<p>Using the computer model and experimental test rig the Stirling engine
generator system will be optimised. The main variable in efficient burner
design is the amount of air supplied to the combustion. As a result of
this the initial investigation will be concerned with the result of going
from a naturally aspirated air supply through to forced convection. This
will be coupled with different levels of recuperation, exhaust heat recovery
and power control. Other areas of interest during the optimisation of the
system are: </p>

<ul>
<ul>
<ol>
<li>Effects of Uneven heating of the cylinder heads of a double acting
configuration </li>

<li>Heat transients in the hot end heat exchangers when changing power
levels. </li>

<li>What is and how does the thermal inertia of the burner and the engine
affect the operation? How can this be minimised or used to best advantage?
</li>

<li>Control of burner through changes in stroke, fuel flow and blower output.
</li>

<li>Emissions Control, are there certain standards to comply with and how
will this effect the burners performance? </li>
</ol>
</ul>
</ul>

<p>As a result of the optimisation it should be possible to define a complete
system for electricity generation and heat utilisation based on a LPG fuelled
Stirling engine. If the system is to be commercially viable it is necessary
for the system to be self regulating, adjusting inputs and outputs depending
on the system requirements at the time, and easy to operate and maintain.
</p>

<p><b>2. PROJECT RESOURCES</b> </p>

<p>The Stirling engine group of the Mechanical engineering department is
working in conjuction with WhisperTech Ltd. WhisperTech will cover material
costs for the building of a test engine. The majority of manufacturing
for the test engine can be performed within the department. The department
has provided required laboratory space and the majority of the computing
resources required to do the modelling and experimental work.. Most of
the computational modelling will be done on a PC based system while some
finite element work may require a more powerful UNIX or VAX system. It
would be desirable to purchase a modern Stirling cycle computer model such
as the GLIMPS package as mentioned previously. </p>

</body>
</html>
</DOC>
