<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Andrew Lintott</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P><A NAME="top"></A></P>

<H1>Andrew Lintott BE(Hons)</H1>

<P><IMG SRC="lintotfa.jpg" HEIGHT=246 WIDTH=173 ALIGN=RIGHT></P>

<H3>University of Canterbury, <BR>
Mechanical Engineering Department</H3>

<P>After my original web page drew world wide condemnation because of its
general tediousness and irrelevance, I felt obliged to react. So here is
the new improved Andrew Lintott page, specifically designed to impress
and astound.</P>

<P>Those with access can upload drafts of my <A HREF="grdunlop/thesis.htm">thesis</A>.
<BR>
</P>

<H4>Who is this guy anyway?</H4>

<P><BR>
I am a doctoral student nearing the end of my research into <B><A HREF="#research">Calibration
of Parallel Topology Robots. <BR>
</A></B>I am also president of the <A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/clubs/latindnc/latindnc.htm">Latin
Dance Club</A> and I'm heavily into dance of several kinds. I also have
a few other <A HREF="#hobbies">hobbies</A>. Perhaps you would like to check
out my <A HREF="lintot2.htm">personal details</A> (or at least those that
I feel inclined to let you see).</P>

<P>
<HR ALIGN=left SIZE=2><A NAME="research"></A></P>

<H4>Calibration of Parallel Topology Robots</H4>

<P>At present, most robots in industrial applications are serial type robots.
These are characterised by a serial joint-link-joint structure and only
one open kinematic chain. Parallel robots are an entirely different class
of mechanism that uses multiple kinematic chains in parallel. As a result
a characteristic of parallel robots is the closed kinematic loops and the
use of passive (non-actuated joints). <BR>
Click on these illustrations of serial and parallel robot topologies to
see them better (142k). <BR>
<A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/ROBOTS.HTM"><IMG SRC="deltasm.jpg" HEIGHT=200 WIDTH=200></A><A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/student/postgrad/ROBOTS.HTM"><IMG SRC="kiwibosm.jpg" HEIGHT=200 WIDTH=200></A>
<BR>
The advantage of parallel robots is the inherent stiffness of the mechanism
and the fact that one can situate the actuators on an immobile base member
(as with the DELTA robot) thereby reducing the mobile mass. A well known
parallel mechanism is the Stewart platform. <BR>
Calibration of robots is necessary if positioning accuracy is an important
consideration in a movement sequence. Most serial robots are only accurate
to the order of millimetres. Calibration can often improve position and
orientation accuracy by an order of magnitude. Similar improvement is expected
with parallel mechanisms.</P>

<H5>Stages of the project that have been completed to date:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>Construction and control of a large scale DELTA robot. </LI>

<LI>Detailed geometric and differential models for the DELTA robot. </LI>

<LI>Simulated calibration of a simple parallel mechanism using linear techniques.
</LI>

<LI>Simulated calibration of a simplified Stewart platform using non-linear
techniques. </LI>
</UL>

<H5>Stages of the project that have yet to be completed:</H5>

<UL>
<LI>Investigation of observability and solvability criteria for parallel
mechanisms. </LI>

<LI>A generalised geometric model for parallel robot calibration.</LI>

<LI>Experimental calibration of the DELTA robot. </LI>
</UL>

<P><A HREF="lintpapr.htm">Papers on the topic and related topics</A></P>

<P><A HREF="#top">Back to top</A> 
<HR ALIGN=left SIZE=2><A NAME="hobbies"></A></P>

<H4>Hobbies and Interests</H4>

<P>As you may have gathered, I spend a lot of time dancing. I have been
a Ballroom dancer since 1989. So far I have sat examinations up to Second
Bar Gold Cross. I have 2 dance partners: Natalie and Justine, both are
top quality women. I've been into Latin Dance for about 4 years. In 1994,
a small group of people (including myself) got together and formed the
<A HREF="http://www.mech.canterbury.ac.nz/clubs/latindnc/latindnc.htm">Latin
Dance Club</A> in order to provide a cheap and friendly place to learn
the dances (Salsa, Cumbia and Merengue). The next year I assumed the President's
post after the first president found a job and left. It's been both a fantastic
experience and a nightmare since I took up the job: lots of work and lots
of things to keep organised and running smoothly. <BR>
I've also done a small bit of Flamenco (a bit hard on the ankles) and,
recently, a bit of CeRock dancing (not so good at that).</P>

<P>Then there's guitar making, which I used to do a lot, but now I have
trouble finding the time for. I make electric guitars (acoustic guitars
are really difficult to make and I haven't got the tools). I've made a
couple of &quot;bitsa&quot; guitars, a Telecaster copy, and a Gibson Les
Paul copy. The GLP sounds pretty good. I used the Gibson L6-S circuitry
because it gives lots of tonal variation. The body and neck are made of
mahogany and I designed and made the bridge out of brass. As a result (and
because I use heavier gauge strings) the sustain is amazing. The guitar
also weighs a ton. The nut is bone because it gives a more mellow sound
than brass, which can sometimes sound twangy. I also have an electric bass
sitting around half finished. <BR>
I play these instruments through a tiny 30W amp that I built as well. It's
amazing how creative you can get if you are too cheap to buy anything.</P>

<P>Last year my friend Hamish and I entered in the annual cardboard boat
race on lake Victoria. Now that was a ball. We were pretty disappointed
that the contestants were allowed to paint their boats in order to seal
them. We had gone to the trouble to design a boat that would float despite
being waterlogged. As a result the boat was quite slow. It floated long
enough to get us across the lake and we reckon it would have taken us quite
a long way further before finally sinking. It was vitally important that
it didn't sink because I couldn't swim at that stage.</P>

<P>A couple of months ago I got sick of not being able to swim so I took
some lessons. It was awesome. The sense of achievement was enormous. I
never learned to swim as a child because I guess I was afraid of the water.
Nowadays I practice swimming at least once a week. <BR>
I've also taken up juggling recently. I spend a lot of time bending over
picking up the balls at the moment. It gets just a bit easier every time.</P>

<P><A HREF="#top">Back to top</A> </P>

</BODY>
