<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=550 cellpadding=0 HEIGHT=70>
<TR>

<TD width=550 ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
 
<hr width=100% nowrap size=2><br>
 <FONT FACE="MS SERIF">   
<!-- END OF HEADERS--------------------------------------------------------------->

<!--CONTENT --------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<a name="transport01"></a>
 <center><FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">
<p><I>N u c l e a r  &nbspW a s t e &nbsp S h i p m e n t   &nbsp U n d e r w a y  </I></font></center>
 
<p>The shipment involving two casks holding 40 glass blocks of extremely radioactive
         nuclear waste containing some 20,500,000 curies of radioactivity, left Cherbourg on Monday 13th January. 


<p><b>Wednesday January 15th:</b><br>
 New Zealand's Foreign Minister, Don McKinnon has released
another statement on the transport in which he says that New
Zealand is "Extremely disappointed" that the shipment will pass
through the South-west Pacific despite his country's making it
clear that they did not want "it to come anywhere near us."  He
also states that "The Japanese Government can be under no illusion
that it will do so [make the transport] aganst the wishes of the
people of the South Pacific."  He reiterated the demand that the
transport remain outside of NZ's EEZ.
 
<p> A decision was taken by the Malaysian government to ban the
transport and demand that it remain outside of its 200 mile EEZ. 
The decision was taken during a meeting of the Cabinet of the
Malaysian government during its weekly meeting and was announced by
the Science, Technology and Environment Minister Law Hieng Ding. 
As an interesting aside, Law apparently stated that as a party to
the NPT and under its Atomic Energy Licensing Act, Malaysia had the
legal right to control the movement of nuclear material within its
national jurisdiction.
 
<p> Despite direct questions from journalists,
COGEMA will not say what it means that the shipment will go via the
"South-west Pacific".  Even with more careful journalists, this is
leading to comments about the "secret" route.

<p><font size=+1><tt><B><a href="prjan14.html">Press Release:</a> &nbsp 14th January 1997 </tt></font>Nuclear waste shipment to go via South Africa and South Pacific.  This late announcement is an insult to en route states - says
Greenpeace</B>

<p><A HREF="transhn.html" onMouseOver="moveover('Transport Main Page'); return true"><img valign=middle width=45 height=36 border=0 src="../icons/ntransh.gif" alt="Transport"></a>
 &nbsp <FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">More details from the Transport Pages...</font>
<br>
<br><hr width=100% nowrap size=2><br>


<a name="krasno"></a>
<FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">

<p><I>A n t i - N u c l e a r  &nbsp R e f e r e n d u m &nbsp  i n &nbsp K r a s n o y a r s k <br> R e g i o n</I></font>

 <p>The referendum will decide the future
         of the RT-2 plant for spent nuclear fuel reprocessing, located in
         Zheleznogorsk city (Krasnoyarsk region). The initiative group, founded
         with the participation of Greenpeace activists, will have to collect  50 thousand signatures to initiate the referendum...

<p><font size=+1><tt><a href="prdec10.html">Press Release:</a> &nbsp 10th December 1996 </tt></font>


<br><hr width=100% nowrap size=2><br>


<!--CONTENT -------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<a name="kostroma"></a>
 <I><FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF"><p>D e m o c r a c y&nbsp i n&nbsp A c t i o n&nbsp i n&nbsp R u s s i a</font></I>
     
     <p>Are we about to witness the beginning of the end of nuclear power in 
     Russia?
     <p>On December 8th, the people of Kostroma  cast their votes in the first ever regional referendum on nuclear power in Russia.  
     <p>When communities in western Europe have been asked about nuclear 
     power, many have said no to new reactors. National referenda have 
     stopped nuclear power programmes in Sweden, Austria, Switzerland and 
     Italy.  While in Asia, Japanese and Taiwanese residents have also 
     voted overwhelming against new reactors in regional referenda.
     Finally a Russian community has been given the opportunity to say no 
     to a reactor being built on it's doorstep. 


<p><font size=+1><tt><a href="prdec09.html">PressRelease:</a> 9th December 1996: &nbspThe people of Kostroma reject Nuclear Power in First Ever Regional Referenda Held in Russia</tt>


<p><A HREF="react.html" onMouseOver="moveover('Reactors Main Page'); return true"><img align=bottom width=40 height=45 border=0 src="../icons/nreacth.gif" alt="Reactors"></a>
 &nbsp <FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">More details from the Reactors Pages...</font>
<br>





<br><hr width=100% nowrap size=2><br>

<!--CONTENT --------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<a name="reactors01"></a>
<p><FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF"><I>C h e r n o b y l &nbsp R e a c t o r   &nbsp  T o  &nbsp C l o s e </I></font>
 

<FONT size=3 FACE="MS SERIF">
<p>Unit 1 of the Chernobyl nuclear power complex was finally closed
            today, implementing a decision of the Ukrainian government taken in
            Moscow at the G7 meeting in April. The decomissioning of the plant is
            being funded by the G7 through a Memorandum of Understanding with
            the Ukrainian government. 
</font>
<p><font size=+1><tt><a href="prnov30.html">Press Release:</a> &nbsp 30th November 1996 </tt></font>

<p><A HREF="react.html" onMouseOver="moveover('Reactors Main Page'); return true"><img align=bottom width=40 height=45 border=0 src="../icons/nreacth.gif" alt="Reactors"></a>
 &nbsp <FONT SIZE=+1 FACE="MS SERIF">More details from the Reactors Pages...</font>


<br><hr width=100% nowrap size=2><br>

   
</TD></TR></TABLE>

</body></html>















