<title>MV Greenpeace Brazilian photobook</title>
</head>

<body>
<h1>Brazil visit photobook</h1> 
<p>
On this page are several photographs and a .WAV or RealAudio file.
These large photo files are high resolution scans and are best 
viewed with an extrenal or spawned .GIF viewer.  
<p>
A page with smaller versions of these and other pictures optimised for viewing
on Netscape is under consruction.
This page is still under construction.
</p>

<br></br>
<a href="rionegro.wav">180KB WAV</a> or 
<a href="rionegro.ram">17KB RealAudio</a>
<IMG SRC="ra.gif" ALT=" sound ">
<b> - Rainforest bird sounds</b> 
recorded on the Rio Negro welcome you.

<br></br>  
<a href="moline5.gif">
<img src="moline5i.gif" alt="Colour photo of">236KB GIF -
Deckhand on the foredeck of the MV Greenpeace </a> flaking the 
mooring lines prior to the ship's arrival in Golfito, Costa Rica.

<br></br>
<a href="transit5.gif">
<img src="transiti.gif" alt="Color photo of the">265KB GIF -  
View from the crows nest of the M/V Greenpeace </a> as it entered
the Malflores locks of the Panama Canal during it's 
transit from Golfito, Costa Rica to Georgetown, Guyana.

<br></br>
<a href="4deck5.gif">
<img src="4deckico.gif" alt="Color photo of">184KB GIF -
The foredeck of the M/V Greenpeace </a> as it makes it way up
the Amazon from Belem to Santarem.  On the left is the anchor 
windlass.  This picture also shows the front of the bridge deck 
where an Orca whale is painted.

<br></br>
<a href="amatwt2.jpg"><img src="amatwt2.gif" alt="Colour photo of ">
326KB JPG - Greeenpeace Helicopter ZK-HOQ</a>, affectionately known as
'Tweety', as it patrols a tributary of the Amazon. 

<br></br>
<a href="biglog5.gif"><img src="biglog_i.gif" alt="Colour photo of ">
230KB GIF - A truck carries a log away</a> from the foreshore In Santarem.  
The <A HREF="fldfrst.html">flooded forests</a> in this region are threatened
by uncontrolled logging practices.

<br></br>
<a href="brasil.gif"><img src="brasil_i.gif" alt="Colour photo of">
237KB GIF - Cut timber awaits loading onto a ship for export.</a>   

<br></br>

<p>
Photos by Thom Looney (radio operator), Bill
Barclay (GPI forest campaigner) and others.
<address>
email: Thom.Looney@green2.greenpeace.org
</address>
