<title>MV Greenpeace in the Antarctic</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Antarctic Whaling</h1>
<pre>
                    ************************
                    GREENPEACE PRESS RELEASE
                    ************************
</pre>
<h3>>> MV GREENPEACE HELICOPTER PILOT SAVES A WHALE</h3>

SOUTHERN OCEAN, ANTARCTICA, 18 February 1995 (GP) As
confrontations between the 
<a href="mvgp.html">MV GREENPEACE</a>
 and the Japanese whaling
fleet <a href="0214kyo2.gif">
<img align=middle src="214kyo2i.gif" alt="(Front view) ">188KB GIF</a> or
<a href="0214kyo2.jpg">57KB JPG,</a>
escalate in the Antarctic whale sanctuary today, 
US citizens aboard the Greenpeace ship called on Vice President Al
Gore to honour his commitment to the sanctuary by protesting to
Japan.
<p>
The MV GREENPEACE crew have saved another minke whale from the
Japanese harpoons in their latest in a week-long series of
confrontations with the whaling fleet in the newly created whale
sanctuary.
<p>
Earlier today, Greenpeace helicopter pilot Paula Huckleberry
found the Japanese catcher boat Toshi Maru No. 18 chasing a minke
whale just ahead of the catcher's bow.
<p>
Exclusive Greenpeace footage shows Huckleberry swooping down
toward the scene, calling the whalers on VHF radio.  
<a href="whaler2.gif">
<img align=top src="whaler2i.gif" alt="Helicopter in front of whaler catcher ">212KB GIF</a> or
<a href="whaler2.jpg">64KB JPG.</a>
<br></br>
"Toshi Maru
No. 18,this is the Greenpeace helicopter on your starboard side,"
Huckleberry told them. "Do not shoot the whale, move your crew
away from the harpoon."
<p>
The whalers quickly lost interest in the hunt and the minke
turned sharply and swam away. 
<p>
Huckleberry is one of five US citizens onboard the MV Greenpeace
who today wrote to US Vice President Al Gore's Internet address,
asking him to formally protest to the Japanese Government.  Vice
President Gore last year publicly backed the establishment of the
Southern Ocean Sanctuary. 
<p>
The sanctuary was created by a vote of 23-1 with Japan completely
isolated, at last year's meeting of the International Whaling
Commission (IWC) in Mexico.  The Japanese fleet has continued its
so-called "scientific" whale hunt -- the meat it produces retails
in Tokyo's markets and restaurants for up to $US160 a pound.  
"Over the past 10 days we have shown the world what the Japanese
whaling fleet does not want it to see -- <br>
<a href="0215nm1.gif">
<img src="0215nm1i.gif" alt="Whale being flensed ">147KB GIF</a> or 
<a href="0215nm1.jpg">44KB JPG</a> minke whales killed in
the name of science but flensed and processed for market," said
Greenpeace whales campaigner Kieran Mulvaney onboard the MV
GREENPEACE.
<p>
"Greenpeace will continue to put ourselves between the whalers
and whales for as long as we can stay here in Antarctica," said
Mulvaney. 
<a href="0215tm18.gif">
<img align=top src="215tm18i.gif" alt="(Front view) ">168KB GIF</a> or
<a href="0215tm18.jpg">51KB JPG,</a>
<br></br>
 "But we obviously can't stop the whale hunt by
ourselves.  It's up to the 23 governments and their citizens who
created the sanctuary this year to convince Japan to stop its
hunt and call back its whaling fleet."
<p>
For more information, please call:
Kieran Mulvaney onboard the MV GREENPEACE ++872 1301346, or 
Desley Mather, Greenpeace Communications ++44 171 833 0600.
<p>
VIDEO FOOTAGE AVAILABLE FROM REUTERS TV AND WTN
<p>
<ul>
<li><a href="nm1.html">
More details on Nisshin Maru</a>, the mother ship of the whaling fleet.</li></ul>
</ul><hr>
