<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> APPEAL TO ALL INTERNET USERS TO STOP ARRIVAL 
OF NEW
CHLORINE PLANT IN UNIQUE NATURE CONSERVATION AREA </TITLE>

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFC8" TEXT="005500" LINK="EF0000" VLINK="8A0000"
ALINK="FF911D"> <br><br> <CENTER> <P><HR WIDTH=600> <br><br> <TABLE
BORDER=0 WIDTH=600><TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER> <FONT SIZE=+2><B>APPEAL TO
ALL INTERNET USERS TO STOP ARRIVAL OF NEW CHLORINE PLANT IN UNIQUE
NATURE CONSERVATION AREA<BR><BR>LATEST UPDATE: December 11: 
 </B></TD></TR></TABLE> <br><br> <center>


<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=450><TR><TD>

<p></FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>The highest administrative court in 
the Netherlands 'Raad van State'
overruled the environmental licences given to the 
American company BF Goodrich. The
court stated that BF Goodrich has to reduce the 
plant's discharge of chlorinated
substances with a factor ten, by lowering the 
standard from 1 mg per liter to 0,1. The 
request for suspension by Greenpeace and the 
Dutch Society for the Preservation of
the Wadden Sea has not been honoured.

<p>BF Goodrich can now build their CPVC 
(postchlorinated PVC) plant, it will be situated
on the edge of the Wadden Sea, an unique 
internationally recognised wetland and nature
conservation area. Environmental groups are 
appalled that the discharge of chlorinated
substances has not been forbidden. An increase in 
emissions of hazardous organochlorines
is contrary to recent internationally made 
agreements such as North Sea Ministers
Conference 1995 to prioritize hazardous 
organochlorines for elimination within one
generation (in other words by 2020). 

<p>During 1997 the 'Raad van State' will deal with 
the appeal of Greenpeace and the Dutch
Society for the Preservation of the Wadden Sea 
opposing the issued environmental
licences.
</font>
</td></tr></table>
<p><center>Return to the <a href="/greenpeace.html"><img
src="../icons/barwhit1.gif"border=0 width=265 height=36></a> home page
<HR WIDTH=600>
</center>
