<title>Press Release</title></head>

<body background="../icons/nukback7.gif" bgcolor="#d03512" text=#000000 link="#008000" alink= "#000099" vlink="#139000">

<center>
<table border=1 width=1050><tr><td><tt><font size=+2><a href="transhn.html"> Press Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases &nbspPress Releases...</a></font></td></tr></table>
<center>
<table border=0 width=600><tr><td><tt> 

<br><br><p><font size=+1>


<!--INSERT TITLE------------------------------------------------------------------------------>



<!--INSERT TITLE------------------------------------------------------------------------------>

<B>NUCLEAR WASTE SHIPMENT TO GO VIA SOUTH AFRICA AND SOUTH PACIFIC.
THIS LATE ANNOUNCEMENT IS AN INSULT TO EN ROUTE STATES - says
GREENPEACE 
</B></font>
 
<!--END TITLE----------------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<!--INSERT DATE,TEXT---------------------------------------------------------------------->

<p><B>AMSTERDAM,  January 14th, 1997 </B>



<p>One day after the departure of their
controversial nuclear waste shipment (1), representatives of the
French, Japanese and British plutonium industries have simply
announced that the transport will go to Japan via South Africa and the
South- West Pacific.  Greenpeace has called the late announcement an
"insult" to foreign nations. Despite protest by countries around the
world and their requests for prior notification and consultation
regarding the shipment, the "Pacific Teal" left Cherbourg on Monday,
January 13th without public disclosure of its route. 

<p>"Given that dozens of nations have demanded prior notification and
consultation regarding this shipment, this after-the-fact announcement
is like an arsonist who yells fire after burning down a house," said
Damon Moglen of Greenpeace International.  "Given the breadth of
concerns raised, this empty gesture is too little and too late to stem
the tide of international protest."

<p>While potential en route nations have demanded prior consultation and
requested basic information about the shipment's routing, safety
provisions, emergency planning, the industry's statement today only
states that the transport will go via "the Cape of Good Hope and the
South-West Pacific" and will arrive in Japan mid-March. 

<p>On Monday the 13th, hours after the transport slipped out of France,
the former French Environmental Minister, Segolene Royale announced
that the shipment posed "unacceptable risks."  Ms. Royale served as
France's Environmental Minister in 1992/93.  

<p>Controversy in France has also been fanned by the publication of new
evidence linking the La Hague plutonium reprocessing plant with
leukaemia cancers in the area around Cherbourg. In the article
published on January 10th in the British Medical Journal, Professor
Viel, the French epidemiologist who conducted the study, suggests that
the plant's radioactive contamination of beaches and local fish and
shellfish may be the cause.

<p>Most immediately threatened by the nuclear waste shipment is France
itself, followed by Spain and Portugal. and then the nations of the
Western African coast.  In February 1995, when France conducted its
first plutonium waste shipment to Japan onboard the British- flagged
"Pacific Pintail", Portuguese and Spanish naval vessels were deployed
to protect their 200-mile exclusive economic zones from the shipment.

<p><B>FOR FURTHER INFORMATION CONTACT:

<P>Damon Moglen: Greenpeace International - Paris +33 1 53438585
<P>OR
<p>Jean-Luc Thierry: Greenpeace France - Cherbourg - +33 233932800
<p> OR
<P>Luisa Colasimone, Greenpeace International Press Desk,  +31 20 52
49 546</B> 

<!--END OF TEXT---------------------------------------------------------------------->

<p>Footage is available from:
<p> WTN, London, +44 171 410 52 71
<br> Reuters, London, +44 181 965 77 33

<br><br><hr width=400 nowrap size=2><br>

<p>Note: 
<P>(1) The British-flagged freighter "Pacific Teal" left the French port
of Cherbourg yesterday with a cargo of forty blocks of glassified high
level nuclear waste bound for Japan.  The cargo of intensely
radioactive plutonium waste is a by-product of the separation of
weapon-usable plutonium from Japanese irradiated nuclear reactor fuel
processed at the French La Hague reprocessing plant.  Each block,
containing 150 litres of glassified fission products, weighs some 490
kilogrammes.  The waste is so intensely radioactive that a person
standing nearby a single unshielded glass block would receive a lethal
dose of radiation in less than 60 seconds.

<P>The transport on the Teal is the second of a series of global waste
shipments involving the movement of over 3,000 blocks of plutonium
waste in the course of the next ten to fifteen years.  Greenpeace has
warned that it expects two more plutonium waste transports from French
to Japan within the next 14 months.

</td></tr></table>

<br><br><hr width=400 nowrap size=2><br>
<table border=0 width=150 cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td align=center>
<!--A HREF="hotnews.html"><img border=0 width=35 height=30 src="../icons/ntog03l.gif"></A-->
</td><td align=center>
<A HREF="#pagetop"><img border=0 width=30 height=30 src="../icons/ntog03.gif"></A>
</td><td align=center>
</td></tr></table>
