<HEAD>
<TITLE>Greenpeace UK Science</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY TEXT="000000" LINK="0000FF" VLINK="8000FF" ALINK="008040" background="icons/smbg.gif">
<!--START PRECAUTIONARY PRINCIPLE TABLE-->
<a name="ra"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width=720>

<tr><td height=72 width=72><img src="icons/blank72.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></td>
<td height=72 width=72><a href="index.html#pp"><img src="icons/neg0.gif" width=72 height=72 border=0></a></td>
<td height=72 valign=center><a href="index.html#pp"><img src="icons/hppt.gif" border=0 width=176 height=30></a></td></tr>

<tr><td width=72></td>
<td width=72></td>
<td valign=center width=576>
<!--INSERT TEXT HERE-->

<P><B>Greenpeace Business April/may 1996</B>


<P><B>Hormone Disrupters: Let the precautionary principle 
prevail</B>

<P>Last month, a book was published in the USA: Our Stolen Future, which analyses a 
range of scientific evidence and concludes that certain synthetic chemicals are acting as 
hormone disrupters - causing serious reproductive problems in wildlife and humans. 
Talked about as the next Silent Spring, the book argues that hormone systems are 
being altered by the build-up in the environment and in our bodies of chemicals found 
in pesticides, plastics and industrial pollutants.

<P>The chemical industry is attempting to undermine the scientific evidence and is fighting 
for continued production of all of these chemicals. Greenpeace will  continue to 
provide the business community with data on the existence of realistic alternatives - 
especially for PVC, responsible for two significant hormone disrupters.

<P>The clear message from Our Stolen Future is, however, much broader and more 
fundamental to the way we live and work in an industrial society. The current 
decision making process - supported by business and government - which 
permits industry to use chemicals even when they are suspected of doing damage 
to the environment and human health, must be radically altered.

<P>A new way of thinking, analysing and acting must be introduced. It is called the 
precautionary principle and has been promoted by Greenpeace for many years. It 
requires that preventative action is taken against harmful chemicals.

<P>The precautionary principle has already been enshrined in international protocols 
including the OSPAR Commission in 1992, the North Sea Ministers Conference 
agreement and the UNEP Washington Declaration last November all of which seek to 
eliminate toxic substances.

<P>Neglect of the precautionary principle has already led to global warming and a 
changing climate; holes in the ozone layer over Antarctica and elsewhere; many 
disorders in marine life, such as seals in the North Sea, linked to persistent chemicals 
such as PCBs. Hormone disrupters (which include some PCBs) are simply the latest 
example. Will the industrial stampede to release genetically manipulated organisms into 
the environment be yet another future disaster our children must overcome?

<P>Chemical producers and the scientific community will continue to debate and disagree 
on the specific products and processes which are causing the most hormone disruption. 
For Greenpeace, the larger issue will be how to convince industry to act responsibly.




</td></tr></table>
<!--END PRECAUTIONARY PRINCIPLE TABLE-->
