<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Background document on Odin</H4>
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<a href="brent.html"><img align=right src="vict02t.gif" border=0></a><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<P><H4>Background document on Odin</h4>


Esso has proposed that the jacket is toppled in situ and used as an artificial reef. The depth of the site is 103 meters, and is 178 kilometres off the coast - west of Bergen. No bottom dwelling fish, only pelagic (mainly cod). The  sea bed is only mud and sand. <P>
 <P>
The Odin platform is a gas installation with a steel jacket. It is fairly small  - 40 x 40 x 112 meters (jacket). On top the drilling equipment, living quarters. Esso propose to take the top ashore for reuse and recycling. The legs of  the jacket is proposed cut at 5 meters ( either with explosives or by mechanical cutting) and then tipped on its side. That leaves 63 meters of water above the  jacket. They do not want to clean the jacket before toppled, and will leave  paint and anodes on the construction and drilling mud beneath it (not very  much) They also want to leave all the pipelines. <P>
 <P>
A scientific institute in Stavanger, Norway says that it will be very  interesting to study the jacket as a reef, and they believe that it might  have a positive effect. They argue that it will protect fish from fishermen, and therefor be of benefit to the marine environment. This group will get 2,8 million dollars for research if Esso are allowed to topple in situ...   <P>

The political attitude towards this is in general very negative. Nobody really  believes that an artificial reef will have an effect in the North Sea - at that  depth, in an area where there are no natural reefs  and very far away from the coastline. <P>
 <P>
Politicians say that if Esso are allowed to dump, they will probably have to remove it and dump it in a deep fjord, not topple it in situ.   <P>
Esso proposes that they have responsibility of  the jacket, if toppled in situ,  for five years, while the research is going on. After that Norway has to take responsibility. This is a proposal the Government is not too happy about this proposal, so it is likely that they will ask Esso to take full responsibility or <P>
as them to dump on a deeper site instead or ... ask them to take it ashore.   <P>

Decision about what will happen to Odin, is taken by the Government today.  They will need a final approval from the Parliament, but due to the political  situation, it is very rear that a proposal from the Government is changed.   <P>



THE ODIN FIELD<P>
 <P>
The Odin field is placed 178 kilometres west off Bergen, and  has one   fully integrated steel installation, with living  quarters and drilling    equipment. The gas is transported  to the Frigg field for processing, and   from there to St. Fergus in Scotland. The field is 100% owned and   operated by Esso Norway. Total investments in the field since the   beginning of the production has been 4.4 million  UK pounds.   <P>
The field was closed down in August 1994, due to lack of further   gas reserves at the field. It had then been  pumping gas for ten years, at a   total amount of 27,7 billion  Sm3. The field was found in 1970, but   production did not start till October 1984. The platform was installed July   1983.  The weld is closed down, the pipeline is blocked in each end,   cleaned and filled with sea water. Nobody is living on the  platform, but   people from Esso is going out to the platform  once a month to look after   it. <P>
 <P>
Esso has made a environmental/economic study for the different   alternatives of what can be done with Odin. They are especially   emphasising that  toppling of the jacket  can have a positive impact as an   artificial reef at the field.  The platform consists of the separate parts, that  
can be handled in different ways. <P>

 
<pre>           Topside              Jacket          Pipeline   
        1. Recycle              Recycle         Recycle 
        2. Recycle              Recycle         Leave 
        3. Recycle              Dump            Leave 
->->->  4. Recycle              Toppling        Leave 
        5. Dump                 Toppling        Leave 
        6. Toppling             Toppling        Leave 
        7. Dump                 Dump            Leave 
 
* Recycle or reused 
->->-> The option Esso asks for allowance to do - ie. topple jacket in situ   
</pre>
It is however clear that Esso will take the topside ashore regardless of   what the Parliament decides. This because they hope that it will be   possible to reuse this part of the  platform. If that is not possible, they will  <P>
recycle it. All  loose equipment will also be removed, in a hope to reuse   it.  <P>
 <P>
Esso has looked into the environmental benefits of recycling in stead of   producing new steel and other  metals, but also how polluting transport of   the different  parts would be. By recycling in stead of producing new metals,  you save between 85 and 95% of use of energy and water and pollution to air,  land and water. <P>
 <P>
They also look into how much they could earn by selling the metals for recycling. <P>
Total  costs for the different alternatives will however look like this:   <P>
Alt. 1. 37,7 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 2. 26,6 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 3. 27,7 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 4. 19,7 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 5. 20,0 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 6. 21,3 million pounds <BR>
Alt. 7. 28,0 million pounds <BR>
<BR>
 
 
So bringing everything ashore will cost about 13 million pound more than  toppling. 7 million to bring the jacket ashore, but to leave the pipeline.  (NB - Numbers have changed since they gave this figure to the  government - estimated costs of removing the jacket now - 3 to 4 million  pound, i.e. half the cost!) <P>
 <P>
Esso will only have to pay part of the costs of decommissioning the   platform.  Norway will pay a certain percentage of the total costs. How   high the percentage will be, depends on how much tax Esso has paid to   Norway during their operational period. This is somewhere between 60   and 70 %. In addition to that Esso can ask for economical help from the   Parliament. There is no fixed rule for how much this can be, but in the   case of Nord Oest Frigg, Norway paid 60 % of the costs (including the   percentage of the tax)  <P>
 <P>
Employment effects of the alternatives <P>

 
Alt.1. 640 people employed for one year <BR>
Alt.2. 560 --------------"--------------- <BR>
Alt.3. 560 --------------"--------------- <BR>
Alt.4. 450 --------------"--------------- <BR>
Alt.5. 430 --------------"--------------- <BR>
Alt.6. 470 --------------"--------------- <BR>
Alt.7. 520 --------------"--------------- <BR>

 <P>
So 190 more jobs by taking everything ashore instead of toppling, like  Esso would like to do. <P>
 <P>
The report states that the best environmental option would be to recycle   all parts of the installation, but that alternative 3 and 4 is fully   environmental acceptable, since the jacket consists of only small amounts   of  toxic chemicals, and that the area in general is not very polluted.  Esso   also states that the fishing ground in the area is not  very commonly used,   and not used at all by Norwegian fishermen. Scottish fishermen are the only   once using the area.  <P>
 <P>
Esso's suggestion of what to do with Odin, is alternative four.(the   cheapest alternative) That includes that the topside is taken a shore for   reuse or recycling, the jacked is toppled in situ and the pipeline is left   where it is. Esso claims that this is the best alternative, since they remove    and recycle the most polluting parts, and that the jacket will be perfect as   an artificial reef. Esso has also offered a scientific institute in Bergen/ Stavanger  1,7 million  pounds to research on the effects of such a reef.    <P>
Esso has send this suggestion to the Department of Energy and Industry.   The suggestion has then been commented on by different parties. After  looking into all different suggestions, the Department send their suggestion to the Parliament who makes the final decision.  The decision in parliament  will probably be taken mid April/beginning of May. <P>
 <P>
When the decision is taken, Esso will give the assignment for   removal/toppling/dumping to a company who can deal with all parts of   the operation (this company might contact sub-operators, but Esso   doesn't care about that. The want the task done) Esso have however   asked for an offer from different companies for the removal operations for   all the options to make sure they are prepared  when the Parliament    decides what shall be done. Esso does not want to say how fast they will   start the operational process after the decision from Parliament, but it is   likely that they will start more or less immediately. <P>
<HR>
Content: <P>
 <P>
The total weight of the platform, including the pipeline,  is 29.011 tons.   The pipeline alone weights 15.082 tons, and is 26400 meters long (dia   20") <P>
 <P>
The Jacket consists of 7000 tons of structural steel, 30 tons of PVC, 133   tons of steel pipes and approx. 207 tons present in anodes(aluminium   anodes). The anodes consist of approx. 3% zinc, in total an amount of 6,2   tons.  The weight of metals like copper, chrome and nickel in the steel is 40   tons. <P>
 <P>
The pipelines consists 6000 tons of structural steel, and  have a   protection shell of asbestos ( 29 tons) and tear (16,6 tons). In addition   the pipeline has a shell of concrete(9000 tons) to heighten the weight. 567   aluminium anodes are still attached to the pipeline, and are estimated to   weight 53,5 tons (originally 100 tons)<P>

Read <a href="odinpr01.html">press release</a> or visit <a href="http://www.oslonett.no/~greenp/odinside.html">Greenpeace Norway Web Site</a> on Odin  (in Norwegian)


 

 





